{"term":"1964","caseName":"Waterman Steamship Corporation v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1964/245","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 26, 1965","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren11/oral_argument_audio/14046","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 245, Waterman Steamship Corporation, Petitioner, versus United States.","start":0,"stop":30.74,"duration":30.74},{"text":"Mr. Solicitor General?","start":30.74,"stop":32.587,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Archibald Cox, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":32.587,"stop":36.44,"duration":3.85},{"text":"I move the admission of Paul Bender, Esquire, one of the assistants in my office for the purpose of arguing the next case.","start":36.44,"stop":44.519,"duration":8.08}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"The motion is granted.","start":44.519,"stop":45.805,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Archibald Cox, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":45.805,"stop":51.433,"duration":5.63}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. McConnell?","start":51.433,"stop":53.539,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":53.539,"stop":58.048,"duration":4.51},{"text":"As one of the counsel of record for the petitioner here, Waterman Steamship Corporation, we feel that we have a case with a very limited yet clear issue and result.","start":58.048,"stop":74.105,"duration":16.06},{"text":"We ought to emphasize the issue because if the issue is kept in proper perspective, we believe then that the result will fall as contended by the petitioner.","start":74.105,"stop":87.199,"duration":13.09},{"text":"This is a tax case and we maintain that it concerns the application of the usual rules on the Internal Revenue Code and the 1939 code is the one that controls this case by determining the cost or the tax basis of property, the original price of which property was adjusted downward in pursuant to a statute passed by Congress, which had a limited purpose and which did not have anything in the statute specifying the tax effect which is the issue before this Court.","start":87.199,"stop":128.881,"duration":41.68},{"text":"It is not concerned with a tax statute per se, but rather with a general statute with rather limited applications, but with no specified tax effects.","start":128.881,"stop":143.358,"duration":14.48},{"text":"However, like any other general statute, it may have tax effects and did have tax effects, but again, it's concerned as we see it, not having specific or specified tax effects in the statute that it is then to be determined and controlled by the usual rules of determining cost under the 1939 code.","start":143.358,"stop":165.989,"duration":22.63},{"text":"We do not think that it is concerned with statutory construction.","start":165.989,"stop":169.941,"duration":3.95},{"text":"We think the statute is rather clear and explicit.","start":169.941,"stop":174.504,"duration":4.56},{"text":"It does not, we think, involve or need a study of the legislative history or legislative environment again because of the face of the statute the meaning and effect is clear.","start":174.504,"stop":189.519,"duration":15.02},{"text":"There are two statutes involved in general.","start":189.519,"stop":192.855,"duration":3.34},{"text":"One, the Merchant Ship Sales Act of 1946 which was enacted or came into effect on March 8, 1946, after a study over about a 2-year period in Congress.","start":192.855,"stop":207.028,"duration":14.17},{"text":"The statute in general related to the disposition after the war, of the vessels that had been constructed and most of them owned by the government during the war.","start":207.028,"stop":218.715,"duration":11.69},{"text":"Now a subsidiary question arose and that was, what would be done to those persons or those corporations that had purchased vessels during the war at the war time cost and that these vessels that were going to be sold after the war were going to be sold at less than war time cost, what adjustment would be made to those individuals who had purchased during the war at a higher price?","start":218.715,"stop":248.403,"duration":29.69}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"To accomplish what purpose?","start":248.403,"stop":250.44,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"To accomplish the purpose Your Honor was to get private shipping or to get shipping back into the private industry in a sense that the conclusion of war most of it would have been owned and in the hands of the government.","start":250.44,"stop":262.666,"duration":12.23},{"text":"Now the question was, what would be the price at which these vessels would be sold to any prospective purchaser?","start":262.666,"stop":271.97,"duration":9.3},{"text":"Keeping in mind in our case Your Honor, Waterman had purchased 18 of these vessels from the Government during the war and purchased them at their cost during the war.","start":271.97,"stop":282.477,"duration":10.51}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":282.477,"stop":283.382,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"After the war, the so-called statutory sales price as set out in the act, would be a lower price than the cost of construction during the war.","start":283.382,"stop":293.769,"duration":10.39},{"text":"Now --","start":293.769,"stop":294.746,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But was it -- my point was this, was it to equate the price of those ships that were purchased during the war with those that were purchased after wards?","start":294.746,"stop":306.208,"duration":11.46}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It was taken to consideration, Your Honor, the fact that the ones purchased in the war had been purchased at a higher price.","start":306.208,"stop":314.05,"duration":7.84}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":314.05,"stop":314.483,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, it did not specify that it would be changed, adjusted to the price at which they would be sold after the war, but rather the statute set out in one section on the Section 9 which pertain to prior sales, section 9B set out the formula to be followed in adjusting the price of those purchased previously during war time.","start":314.483,"stop":338.247,"duration":23.76},{"text":"Now, we say here that the statute is clear.","start":338.247,"stop":341.22,"duration":2.97},{"text":"I don't think there's any arguing with the Government as to how to apply.","start":341.22,"stop":344.963,"duration":3.74},{"text":"The issue facing the Court here is the effect of that adjustment provided under the statute on the cost or tax basis of these vessels whose prices were adjusted down.","start":344.963,"stop":356.632,"duration":11.67}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But does the question of whether the price of these ships that were purchased during the war and those after the war were the same after the formula was applied or not?","start":356.632,"stop":372.823,"duration":16.19}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We maintain that they're not the same Your Honor.","start":372.823,"stop":375.08,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"They're not the same?","start":375.08,"stop":376.053,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":376.053,"stop":376.389,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":376.389,"stop":376.537,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We can show that and we feel that that's the heart of this issue, is that we can show that under the normal code rules, the basis of property for depreciation purpose, and that's the question here, is the cost of that property to the taxpayer, the taxpayer's economic investment.","start":376.537,"stop":395.051,"duration":18.51},{"text":"Now, that's the normal code rule.","start":395.051,"stop":397.472,"duration":2.42},{"text":"Now, there's nothing specific in the statute that says that that normal code rule will not apply here.","start":397.472,"stop":404.751,"duration":7.28},{"text":"There's nothing specific in the statute that says, the price after the adjustment is the statutory sales price.","start":404.751,"stop":412.858,"duration":8.11},{"text":"The statute simply sets out a formula for determining an adjustment in price.","start":412.858,"stop":421.855,"duration":9},{"text":"There's no argument about this adjustment.","start":421.855,"stop":424.385,"duration":2.53},{"text":"Now, we say that thereafter it's a simple matter of mathematics.","start":424.385,"stop":428.498,"duration":4.11},{"text":"It was stipulated here and agreed what the basis of the property was prior to the adjustment.","start":428.498,"stop":435.207,"duration":6.71},{"text":"It is stipulated and agreed here what the adjustment was.","start":435.207,"stop":438.964,"duration":3.76},{"text":"It's stipulated and agreed here what is the basis after the judgment except on the tax basis.","start":438.964,"stop":446.633,"duration":7.67},{"text":"Now, we say though applying the normal 1939 Internal Revenue Code Rule that you will come up here with a basis of approximately $26 million as contended by petitioner as against the approximately $17 to $18 million contended by the Government.","start":446.633,"stop":464.917,"duration":18.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Then we can approach the case as far you're concerned on the basis that the relative cost of the ships that were purchased during the war and those that were purchased after wards is immaterial?","start":464.917,"stop":480.737,"duration":15.82}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- that's right sir.","start":480.737,"stop":481.865,"duration":1.13},{"text":"We maintain that the statute does not provide though the prices of the vessels purchased during the war and whose prices are adjusted are adjusted to the statutory sales price, that's correct sir.","start":481.865,"stop":494.991,"duration":13.13},{"text":"Our contention is they are not adjusted to the statutory sales price.","start":494.991,"stop":499.361,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. McConnell, do you agree that this transaction has to be unwind?","start":499.361,"stop":503.511,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":503.511,"stop":504.087,"duration":0.58},{"text":"We do not believe that this is an unwinding transaction.","start":504.087,"stop":507.064,"duration":2.98},{"text":"We believe that's an adjustment transaction that an unwinding --","start":507.064,"stop":511.93,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"How much depreciation did you take on all -- the total depreciation that you take on these 18 vessels up until the time of the price adjusted?","start":511.93,"stop":521.167,"duration":9.24},{"text":"It is about $10 million or $11 million somewhere in --","start":521.167,"stop":523.033,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the figures that were quoted in the Government's brief are correct because they're taken except for the final from the record here which indicated some $11 million at one time.","start":523.033,"stop":535.124,"duration":12.09},{"text":"That -- that we do not contend that we had not taken that amount of appreciation prior to the adjustment.","start":535.124,"stop":543.442,"duration":8.32},{"text":"However, we say this that the adjustment under 9(b) is one adjustment.","start":543.442,"stop":550.506,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do you think you should have gotten the income taxes back that you paid before this, before the adjustment or not?","start":550.506,"stop":556.48,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't think that we got them back Your Honor.","start":556.48,"stop":558.252,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do you think you should have?","start":558.252,"stop":561.23,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we think this that we had to follow the conditions as outlined in the act in order to get the adjustment --","start":561.23,"stop":565.985,"duration":4.75}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Which requires you to get them back, get the tax back, isn't it?","start":565.985,"stop":569.077,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":569.077,"stop":569.532,"duration":0.46},{"text":"We do not interpret Your Honor that it requires us to get the tax back or that we got the tax back.","start":569.532,"stop":576.117,"duration":6.58},{"text":"It is simply --","start":576.117,"stop":576.715,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think it requires you to get the return of charter hire?","start":576.715,"stop":580.987,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":580.987,"stop":581.849,"duration":0.86},{"text":"We don't think that.","start":581.849,"stop":582.767,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think it requires you to be paid for your -- what you would have earned on all these vessels if you --","start":582.767,"stop":589.898,"duration":7.13}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is a part of the credits and --","start":589.898,"stop":592.29,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't think you are entitled any credits before the Act went into effect?","start":592.29,"stop":597.473,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Entitled any credits before that or you mean for transaction?","start":597.473,"stop":600.493,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Up to the period of the time you bought the vessels up to the price adjustment statute, are you entitled to any credits at all --?","start":600.493,"stop":606.775,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":606.775,"stop":607.419,"duration":0.64},{"text":"We entitled to all the credits that the Section 9(b) gives us.","start":607.419,"stop":610.707,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What are they?","start":610.707,"stop":611.439,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":611.439,"stop":611.925,"duration":0.49},{"text":"The first credit is the one for the excess cash payments over 25% that's sub paragraph one.","start":611.925,"stop":619.155,"duration":7.23},{"text":"Another credit is for 3 1/2% interests on that excess cash payments from the date of payments.","start":619.155,"stop":625.153,"duration":6}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Why is that Mr. McConnell?","start":625.153,"stop":628.595,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the statutory formula which the --","start":628.595,"stop":630.801,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah, but why is it?","start":630.801,"stop":632.489,"duration":1.69},{"text":"Why -- why do you suppose that is the formula?","start":632.489,"stop":635.072,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think now undoubtedly Mr. Justice White that the original legislation intended that this go down to the statutory sales price.","start":635.072,"stop":645.154,"duration":10.08},{"text":"In fact, the Senate Bill, the amendment of this would have adjusted this down and any taxpayer taken an adjustment would have received the difference between the purchase price before the Act and the statutory sales price.","start":645.154,"stop":662.106,"duration":16.95},{"text":"He would have gotten that completely without giving any credits, tax or otherwise, although he would have it returned to the government everything over 15% of the statutory sales price as far as charter had, but that was not the act that was passed.","start":662.106,"stop":680.469,"duration":18.36},{"text":"Now, this was amended and they set up this morning.","start":680.469,"stop":683.881,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So the Act -- the Act expressly requires that the party goes through some adjustment procedures with regard to the period prior to the price of yesterday?","start":683.881,"stop":695.51,"duration":11.63}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"One adjustment Your Honor, it requires an adjustment in price, that's what all of the Section 9 (b) speaks off is an adjustment in price.","start":695.51,"stop":704.364,"duration":8.85},{"text":"Now, we say that any sale or any purchase, who purchases property by certain price, he gets an adjustment.","start":704.364,"stop":713.517,"duration":9.15},{"text":"Now, that adjustment maybe based on a thousand different computations, but he ends up with an adjustment in price which he applies to the original price and then he gets his adjusted price.","start":713.517,"stop":725.471,"duration":11.95},{"text":"Now that's what we say here.","start":725.471,"stop":727.48,"duration":2.01},{"text":"You start out with the original price.","start":727.48,"stop":730.394,"duration":2.91},{"text":"You have an adjustment in price.","start":730.394,"stop":732.851,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the statutory, is the statutory sales price under the new Act you were supposed to pay something like how much?","start":732.851,"stop":740.133,"duration":7.28}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, these vessels statutory sales price of the 18 vessels would have been slightly less than $18 million.","start":740.133,"stop":746.567,"duration":6.43}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"$18 million.","start":746.567,"stop":747.864,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":747.864,"stop":748.138,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's a statutory price.","start":748.138,"stop":749.558,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's a statutory price.","start":749.558,"stop":750.674,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And prior to the time of the establishment of this price you would have taken approximately $11 million worth of depreciation?","start":750.674,"stop":760.295,"duration":9.62}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right sir.","start":760.295,"stop":760.871,"duration":0.58},{"text":"We had also paid approximately $16 million in cash and still that -- oh, after the adjustment.","start":760.871,"stop":766.492,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Just a minute, you say you took $11 million for depreciation prior to the establishment of this price and you want your basis to remain at 26, so that in the long run you want to say that you could take $26 million plus $11, the $38 million in depreciation against vessels which cost you $18 million.","start":766.492,"stop":795.6,"duration":29.11}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we think that --","start":795.6,"stop":797.087,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right or not?","start":797.087,"stop":798.651,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well of course, the $11 million is actual depreciation as I recall and the $26 million would still be whatever the tax rate of that amount.","start":798.651,"stop":806.268,"duration":7.62}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, well I know, but you still want to be able to take $26 million of depreciation, that's what this fight is all about.","start":806.268,"stop":812.316,"duration":6.05}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We would take depreciation on a basis after the adjustment of $26 million, that's right.","start":812.316,"stop":816.516,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And you've already had 11.","start":816.516,"stop":818.668,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We had taken approximately 11 prior to the adjustment that's right, but as -- along that line, I would like to emphasize this fact as to what we think the cost of these vessels and what we think the record indicates clearly is the cost of these vessels to this tax player and the economic investment of this taxpayer in these vessels.","start":818.668,"stop":845.86,"duration":27.19},{"text":"Now, prior to the enactment of the act, prior to the adjustment, it is stipulated that the basis of these 18 vessels, the cost to this taxpayer was slightly in excess of $47 million dollars and I believe that there has been distributed to Your Honors two computations here, single sheets, asked the clerk to, to indicating this breakdown.","start":845.86,"stop":874.184,"duration":28.32},{"text":"First, it shows that total cash payment and the trade in allowances on these 18 vessels up to the day before the Act, the day preceding that.","start":874.184,"stop":884.539,"duration":10.36},{"text":"Now, the adjustment was made many years later, but as other day to the Act.","start":884.539,"stop":889.718,"duration":5.18},{"text":"This taxpayer had paid in cash or trade in for these vessels $16,411,000.","start":889.718,"stop":897.54,"duration":7.82},{"text":"Now, the remaining mortgage and indebtedness on date, this is before the adjustment, was $30,737,000.","start":897.54,"stop":905.595,"duration":8.06},{"text":"Now, we applied to the commissioner for an adjustment in price, an adjustment in price on 18 vessels.","start":905.595,"stop":913.377,"duration":7.78},{"text":"Now, the adjustment was branded under Section 9 (b), an adjustment price.","start":913.377,"stop":923.342,"duration":9.97},{"text":"This adjustment reduced that mortgage indebtedness from $30 million to $10 million, a $20 million reduction and price all in the mortgage indebtedness.","start":923.342,"stop":937.079,"duration":13.74},{"text":"Now we say that you subtract that $20 million from the $47 million basis prior to the adjustment and the cost of this taxpayer is the $16 million odd paid prior to the adjustment, the $10 million odd mortgage indebtedness remaining after the adjustment or as I said, taking the original cost subtracting the adjustment, leaves a basis of $26 million.","start":937.079,"stop":966.195,"duration":29.12},{"text":"Now we say that that follows not because we necessarily want it that way, but because that's the way the statute prescribes, that's all the statute prescribes.","start":966.195,"stop":978.875,"duration":12.68},{"text":"The statute did not prescribe that the basis would be the statutory sales price.","start":978.875,"stop":984.048,"duration":5.17},{"text":"The statute simply prescribes an adjustment in price.","start":984.048,"stop":989.262,"duration":5.21},{"text":"This taxpayer received that adjustment.","start":989.262,"stop":992.203,"duration":2.94},{"text":"We maintain then that you look back to the usual 1939 Code Provisions to then see what is the cost of the property.","start":992.203,"stop":1002.443,"duration":10.24}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Arriving after the adjustment, however, would you apply this $20,468 million in arriving at that adjustment, that's the result -- that's the net result of a computation, isn't it?","start":1002.443,"stop":1017.343,"duration":14.9}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The formula has several computations.","start":1017.343,"stop":1019.507,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you take exception to the figures on page 7 of the Government's brief.","start":1019.507,"stop":1025.654,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Very much so.","start":1025.654,"stop":1026.435,"duration":0.78},{"text":"We think that there is no basis in the language or the structure.","start":1026.435,"stop":1031.739,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how do you arrive at the $20,468 million?","start":1031.739,"stop":1035.223,"duration":3.48},{"text":"You just don't pick it out of the air, you must calculate it somehow?","start":1035.223,"stop":1039.863,"duration":4.64}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1039.863,"stop":1040.509,"duration":0.65},{"text":"It's calculated.","start":1040.509,"stop":1042.233,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that calculation in your brief?","start":1042.233,"stop":1045.544,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In our brief -- it's not in the brief, it's in the appendices and in records though Your Honor.","start":1045.544,"stop":1050.236,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well where?","start":1050.236,"stop":1056.921,"duration":6.68}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If Your Honor will turn in the appendices to appendix E, the computations that are there and if you look on E2 under number 6, total mortgage adjustments which is taken as indicated there from the page 48 of the record, which is a stipulation between the parties.","start":1056.921,"stop":1084.476,"duration":27.56}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but what I want to know is that adjustment in mortgage indebtedness that 24.68, where does that 24.68 come from?","start":1084.476,"stop":1091.655,"duration":7.18}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright, if you'll look there Your Honor at E2 at Computation 6, it gives a balance of the original mortgage indebtedness as of March 7, 1946, that's the day before the act.","start":1091.655,"stop":1103.591,"duration":11.94},{"text":"This is stipulated in the record page 41.","start":1103.591,"stop":1106.274,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"We understand that, but now how about -- where do you get the 17 up there?","start":1106.274,"stop":1110.814,"duration":4.54}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright sir.","start":1110.814,"stop":1111.44,"duration":0.63},{"text":"That is taken right out of sub paragraph 2 of the act on the adjustment which reads as follows.","start":1111.44,"stop":1120.758,"duration":9.32},{"text":"The applicant's indebtedness under any mortgage of the United States with respect to the vessel shall be adjusted.","start":1120.758,"stop":1126.397,"duration":5.64},{"text":"And the next sub paragraph says, the adjusted mortgage indebtedness shall be an amount equal to the excess of the statutory sales price of the vessel as of the day of enactment of this act over the sum of the cash payment retained by the United States under paragraph one.","start":1126.397,"stop":1143.852,"duration":17.46},{"text":"Now paragraph one says, you'll pay 25% statutory sales price.","start":1143.852,"stop":1148.174,"duration":4.32},{"text":"So if you didn't have any trade in, the mortgage would be 75%.","start":1148.174,"stop":1152.94,"duration":4.77},{"text":"Now if you -- then we get to $17 million by the fact of looking at what the -- let me just turn to the record here, Justice White if you'll turn to page 68 in the record.","start":1152.94,"stop":1174.466,"duration":21.53},{"text":"This is a schedule which was attached to the agreement between the government and the petitioner.","start":1174.466,"stop":1185.946,"duration":11.48},{"text":"Actually if you look at page 67 that's a double page there, if you'll notice at the top, original purchase price, line one last column is total all vessels, it has $49 million.","start":1185.946,"stop":1200.592,"duration":14.65},{"text":"Then the next line, less there is no trade in allowance, then, the next line reads less balance of original mortgages up to 03/08/46, that's the day before that shows that the mortgage balance on that day was $30 million.","start":1200.592,"stop":1214.383,"duration":13.79},{"text":"Now, when you take -- then next, you notice, it says less 25% of adjusted statutory sales price, that's the cash you're supposed to pay, then that next line three leaves the excess cash payments.","start":1214.383,"stop":1227.401,"duration":13.02},{"text":"Now if you turn over on 68, it gives the mortgage adjustment, starting with line 13 at the top.","start":1227.401,"stop":1234.674,"duration":7.27},{"text":"Adjusted statutory sales price so forth less 25, then line 16 adjusted mortgages as of 03/08/46.","start":1234.674,"stop":1244.465,"duration":9.79},{"text":"Then line 20 says reduction in mortgage indebtedness $20 million.","start":1244.465,"stop":1251.343,"duration":6.88},{"text":"Now that's where we get, if you take the $13 million adjusted mortgage in line 16, subtract it from your mortgage indebtedness over on the third line on the preceding page of $30 million, that's where you get to $17 million and it's in accordance with a statutory point.","start":1251.343,"stop":1273.447,"duration":22.1}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this involves then on page 67, the United States returning income taxes and the applicants are the returning charter hire.","start":1273.447,"stop":1288.173,"duration":14.73},{"text":"This is all figured in?","start":1288.173,"stop":1290.161,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We do not -- there's no return of charter hire, Your Honor, it's a credit.","start":1290.161,"stop":1296.521,"duration":6.36}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that, it's an offset.","start":1296.521,"stop":1298.236,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a credit.","start":1298.236,"stop":1299.461,"duration":1.22},{"text":"That's the language of the statute.","start":1299.461,"stop":1301.113,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1301.113,"stop":1301.636,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's what in other words in Section 9 (b) you have several credits which must be netted together.","start":1301.636,"stop":1309.751,"duration":8.12},{"text":"Now that's a reason we disagree with --","start":1309.751,"stop":1311.517,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that and you think that the United States in the whole process shouldn't demand back the new depreciation [Inaudible]","start":1311.517,"stop":1320.615,"duration":9.1}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice White, we stand that on this premise that the statute allowed us these credits and Section 9(c)(1), which has limited effect said that you would take that adjustment from the original purchase price and the result would be the adjusted purchase price and we say the tax basis.","start":1320.615,"stop":1344.504,"duration":23.89},{"text":"Now, we're not arguing with the philosophy of the act.","start":1344.504,"stop":1347.397,"duration":2.89},{"text":"We just say we take the act as passed by Congress and you apply the act, and we don't' argue about the adjustment between us.","start":1347.397,"stop":1356.712,"duration":9.32},{"text":"It's simply on the effect and we say that the act does not specify the basics.","start":1356.712,"stop":1363.935,"duration":7.22},{"text":"And therefore, you go to the 1939 Code Provision and there's a sheet before your justices will indicate, this taxpayer paid $26 million for these vessels after the adjustment and this taxpayer is seeking no more than every other taxpayer and that is to be allowed to depreciate those vessels on the remaining life on that cost and that economic investment.","start":1363.935,"stop":1390.195,"duration":26.26}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1390.195,"stop":1396.415,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as we pointed out, Your Honor, if they give them an adjustment that's up to Congress.","start":1396.415,"stop":1403.457,"duration":7.04},{"text":"Congress gave us the adjustment and we say that Congress left to the normal rule how the basis would be computing and the normal rule say that it's $26 million.","start":1403.457,"stop":1415.58,"duration":12.12}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1415.58,"stop":1439.48,"duration":23.9}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we pointed out in one of the footnotes, a case similar to that, although actually as it turned out that they didn't adjust it, they wrote a new contract.","start":1439.48,"stop":1447.536,"duration":8.06},{"text":"Now, we say that then the net effect of that adjustment would be determined under the normal rules and that would be the basis.","start":1447.536,"stop":1458.227,"duration":10.69},{"text":"In other words, if you bought it for $100 and it gave a price adjustment of $20 and the new cost would be $80.","start":1458.227,"stop":1466.594,"duration":8.37},{"text":"And it wouldn't matter, and this is what we think is a key to Mr. Justice White, it wouldn't matter, how you arrived with the $20.","start":1466.594,"stop":1473.893,"duration":7.3},{"text":"You might say now, you earned income of $10, you paid taxes of $2, you had a -- you paid property taxes or something else, or you say I will give you $1 for every child you have.","start":1473.893,"stop":1487.383,"duration":13.49},{"text":"That's part of the computation and you end up with $20.","start":1487.383,"stop":1490.279,"duration":2.9},{"text":"It doesn't matter what the factor that you use to measure the adjustment.","start":1490.279,"stop":1496.199,"duration":5.92},{"text":"The key thing is the amount of adjustment you apply that to the price and the result is your basis, regardless of how it was computed.","start":1496.199,"stop":1505.153,"duration":8.95},{"text":"Now that's our contingent.","start":1505.153,"stop":1506.614,"duration":1.46},{"text":"We say you take Section 9 (b) which has a point made up of several factors of several computations, but it doesn't' matter what they are measured by.","start":1506.614,"stop":1518.404,"duration":11.79},{"text":"You take them and as a result of the adjustment, one single adjustment.","start":1518.404,"stop":1524.994,"duration":6.59},{"text":"You simply either subtract that from the original purchase price to give you a new price or you can do it in a reverse as we we did on this sheet show how much had been paid before, what was the adjusted mortgage indebtedness, the sum of the two would be the basis of property for depreciation.","start":1524.994,"stop":1542.331,"duration":17.34},{"text":"Now, we do not think that it has any unwinding involved, that was a statute that was rejected.","start":1542.331,"stop":1550.004,"duration":7.67},{"text":"An adjustments is not an unwinding.","start":1550.004,"stop":1553.223,"duration":3.22},{"text":"An adjustment confirms the original purchase.","start":1553.223,"stop":1557.193,"duration":3.97},{"text":"In fact in the contract itself, this is recognized and in the regulations issued by maritime that they would have to execute an addendum to the original contracts of purchase.","start":1557.193,"stop":1570.524,"duration":13.33},{"text":"This adjustment was an addendum to the original contracts of purchase and as we point out in our brief, the original contracts of purchase said that we would have the benefit of any legislation that might be passed after the purchase that allowed the same vessels to be sold as subsequent purchases at lower prices.","start":1570.524,"stop":1590.951,"duration":20.43},{"text":"Now, that was an original contract, but we say that there is not unwinding and we say particular that the table as contained in the brief of the government on page 7 has no basis whatsoever in the statute.","start":1590.951,"stop":1607.574,"duration":16.62},{"text":"There's no place to determining a gross price adjustment and as we point out in our reply brief, if they want to use the term gross price adjustment as they've done on line 3 on page 7, then they should call the last line the net price adjustment.","start":1607.574,"stop":1624.011,"duration":16.44},{"text":"That's exactly the -- that's the price adjustment that we receive as indicated in their own schedule one $20 million.","start":1624.011,"stop":1633.025,"duration":9.01},{"text":"That's exactly the price adjustment that we receive, you subtract that from the original price and that gives you the adjusted purchase price and the basis here for depreciation purposes thereafter.","start":1633.025,"stop":1647.624,"duration":14.6},{"text":"No new mortgages were executed.","start":1647.624,"stop":1649.869,"duration":2.24},{"text":"No new notes were executed.","start":1649.869,"stop":1651.338,"duration":1.47},{"text":"The same mortgages were simply adjusted.","start":1651.338,"stop":1653.93,"duration":2.59},{"text":"The same notes were simply adjusted as the payment in the future, so that there is not either a rescission nor is there an unwinding.","start":1653.93,"stop":1664.084,"duration":10.15},{"text":"Now, we also maintain that Section and I might touch on it here, the Section 9 (c) (1) this goes back to Justice White's question, that 9 (c) (1) explicitly provides that this adjustment will be applied against the original purchase price.","start":1664.084,"stop":1683.888,"duration":19.8},{"text":"This is in the condition section.","start":1683.888,"stop":1686.732,"duration":2.84},{"text":"The credits that I was discussing with Mr. Justice White are in the adjustment Section, but the condition Section says that you will for federal tax purposes treat as if certain things had not been done.","start":1686.732,"stop":1700.109,"duration":13.38},{"text":"That carried us back to the original purchase price.","start":1700.109,"stop":1704.943,"duration":4.83},{"text":"You then apply the adjustment on the 9 (b) and you come up with a net result of approximately $26 million.","start":1704.943,"stop":1713.096,"duration":8.15},{"text":"The government would contend that the statute says you must come down to the statutory sales price, but that is not in the statute.","start":1713.096,"stop":1722.908,"duration":9.81},{"text":"The statute simply contains a formula.","start":1722.908,"stop":1726.178,"duration":3.27},{"text":"The result of which is one adjustment in price, and the result of that to this taxpayer is work it either way.","start":1726.178,"stop":1735.103,"duration":8.92},{"text":"Original cost $47 million adjustment and mortgage indebtedness or in price $20 million a little more, the result a basis or a cost or an economic investment of $26 million or I will look at the other way.","start":1735.103,"stop":1753.351,"duration":18.25},{"text":"This taxpayer had paid $16 million the day before this act was passed.","start":1753.351,"stop":1758.171,"duration":4.82},{"text":"The statutory sales price was only $17 million.","start":1758.171,"stop":1762.221,"duration":4.05},{"text":"Now, it's still old $10 million more after the adjustment.","start":1762.221,"stop":1767.094,"duration":4.87},{"text":"Yet the government says you're going to have a basis slightly in excess of the cash already paid without looking at the remaining obligation.","start":1767.094,"stop":1776.501,"duration":9.41},{"text":"So that we say that anyway you look at it on dollars and cents as Judge Patton said in the Court of Claims in Sekone case, Government is saying it's not a dollars and cents, real actual economic cost, but a hypothetical.","start":1776.501,"stop":1792.483,"duration":15.98},{"text":"And we say that the statute does not require that and that the normal code rule justified the basis in fact is the only result of the basis as contended by the taxpayer.","start":1792.483,"stop":1809.508,"duration":17.03},{"text":"Your Honor, there's nothing in the legislative history at all on tax basis, nothing on tax basis and I don't think the government haven't come up with any, we haven't found any.","start":1809.508,"stop":1821.499,"duration":11.99},{"text":"We think too that pulling out a context just one phrase in 9(b) about treating the vessel as if it was sold on the date of the enactment of the act and not before.","start":1821.499,"stop":1833.903,"duration":12.4},{"text":"The government read that in allowing them to do anything to equalize the price depreciation of what not.","start":1833.903,"stop":1844.381,"duration":10.48},{"text":"We simply say no.","start":1844.381,"stop":1846.44,"duration":2.06},{"text":"The formula was Congress' idea of exactly how that was being done by treating the vessel as if it was sold on the date of enactment act and not before and the formula carried that out and it's not for the government now to try to change the formula to come back to what they call the Congressional intent or legislative intent.","start":1846.44,"stop":1866.586,"duration":20.15},{"text":"But to answer your question Mr. Justice Harlan on this age Mr. Justice Harlan, we do not think there's anything in the legislative history on tax basis, but if there's a resort to legislative history and we do not think it's necessary.","start":1866.586,"stop":1878.934,"duration":12.35},{"text":"We think that statute is clear and unambiguous.","start":1878.934,"stop":1882.843,"duration":3.91},{"text":"There's no necessity to legislative history, but if it is, it supports petitioner, both legislative history prior to that and the legislative history subsequent to the act supports the position of the petitioner here.","start":1882.843,"stop":1897.345,"duration":14.5},{"text":"And I would like to reserve the remaining time if I may unless there's some other questions at this time for rebuttal after the government's argument.","start":1897.345,"stop":1907.562,"duration":10.22},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1907.562,"stop":1911.48,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bender.","start":1911.48,"stop":1924.061,"duration":12.58}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice May it Please the Court.","start":1924.061,"stop":1929.713,"duration":5.65},{"text":"In the course of my argument, I'm inescapably going to have to refer the figures.","start":1929.713,"stop":1934.201,"duration":4.49},{"text":"All of them I think are set out on the chart on page 7 of the Government's brief except for the depreciation figure which Mr. Justice White mentioned in his question earlier.","start":1934.201,"stop":1945.395,"duration":11.19},{"text":"I think it will be easier to follow the argument if you have those figures before you.","start":1945.395,"stop":1950.157,"duration":4.76},{"text":"I'll try to make them as simple as possible and round them out.","start":1950.157,"stop":1953.483,"duration":3.33},{"text":"I may have to give some other examples involving different figures in an attempt to make it simple.","start":1953.483,"stop":1959.041,"duration":5.56},{"text":"I shall do my best.","start":1959.041,"stop":1962.69,"duration":3.65},{"text":"Well, let me start this way in the few minutes remaining, I would like to try to demonstrate to you why the petitioner's argument as he stated today is absolutely untenable and I would like to do so this way.","start":1962.69,"stop":1978.274,"duration":15.58},{"text":"Referring again to the chart on page 7, petitioner argues and he said it several times in the brief and he says it in his argument that the statute should be read as having no tax effect.","start":1978.274,"stop":1993.258,"duration":14.98},{"text":"Any mention of taxes in the statute just for the purposes of computing the adjustment, but it has no tax effects and he says that no taxes were returned to him as a consequence of the statute.","start":1993.258,"stop":2005.73,"duration":12.47},{"text":"Well, we think that's wrong and I shall try to demonstrate in the bulk of my argument tomorrow, why the statute does have tax effects and why the fact that the statute has tax effects leads you to the government's results?","start":2005.73,"stop":2021.173,"duration":15.44},{"text":"Well, I should like to take the case first on the assumption that he's right and that the statute has no tax effects.","start":2021.173,"stop":2028.807,"duration":7.63},{"text":"Listen to what his argument is.","start":2028.807,"stop":2030.99,"duration":2.18},{"text":"He said he paid and he did pay about $47 million with each ships, that's on line 1 on page 7.","start":2030.99,"stop":2039.612,"duration":8.62},{"text":"He got back in one way or another, either by cash credit or reduction of his mortgage about $20 million, $20,400,000, that's the net payment on line 10 on the brief.","start":2039.612,"stop":2052.244,"duration":12.63},{"text":"He paid $47 million.","start":2052.244,"stop":2053.55,"duration":1.31},{"text":"He says he got back $20 million, he says his economic investment, then his $26 million, that's the last line of the sheet that he gives you here, remember your graph sheet.","start":2053.55,"stop":2066.851,"duration":13.3},{"text":"Let's assume that's true.","start":2066.851,"stop":2068.116,"duration":1.26},{"text":"His economic investment would be $26 million, but he also concedes that he has already taken depreciation on these ships of about $11 million.","start":2068.116,"stop":2078.788,"duration":10.67},{"text":"He's deducted $11 million from his income for income tax purposes in calculating his taxable income, yes.","start":2078.788,"stop":2087.317,"duration":8.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How much [Inaudible]","start":2087.317,"stop":2090.617,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we say he is allowed for future depreciation of about $17 million, which if you add it to the $11 million would mean that he'd get a total depreciation of $26 million, which he says is just as economic investments.","start":2090.617,"stop":2105.668,"duration":15.05},{"text":"$11 plus oh, excuse me about 28, right, which would be more.","start":2105.668,"stop":2109.853,"duration":4.18},{"text":"We are not being that general because I'm simply -- I'm trying to follow it on his argument.","start":2109.853,"stop":2114.494,"duration":4.64},{"text":"I'm trying to demonstrate why his is wrong.","start":2114.494,"stop":2116.13,"duration":1.64},{"text":"We don't agree with --","start":2116.13,"stop":2117.422,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't [Inaudible]","start":2117.422,"stop":2120.991,"duration":3.57}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"In the future, about $17 million.","start":2120.991,"stop":2124.597,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2124.597,"stop":2129.353,"duration":4.76}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the $11 million has been disallowed Mr. Justice Brennan and his taxes for all those years have been recomputed, so that $11 million dollars was not allowable, that's in Section --","start":2129.353,"stop":2138.162,"duration":8.81}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2138.162,"stop":2139.144,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he once got it, but it was all taken away from him.","start":2139.144,"stop":2141.379,"duration":2.24},{"text":"It can actually --","start":2141.379,"stop":2142.402,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] why did you take it back?","start":2142.402,"stop":2143.524,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly, but he said that that never happens.","start":2143.524,"stop":2146.6,"duration":3.08},{"text":"So, what I'm trying to demonstrate is why his is absolutely wrong and why his gives him a terribly unjustifiable tax benefit.","start":2146.6,"stop":2153.077,"duration":6.48},{"text":"Coming back to what I said, he says his economic investment is $26 million, but he says his basis now is $26 million, which would mean that in the future he can depreciate $26 million.","start":2153.077,"stop":2162.618,"duration":9.54},{"text":"And he also admits that he's a ready depreciated $11 million and he says that depreciation has never been taken away.","start":2162.618,"stop":2168.776,"duration":6.16},{"text":"That would mean that in the future he gets $26 million depreciation, he has already had $11 million depreciation, he gets $37 million -- $37 million depreciation on a total economic investment by his own admission of $26 million, now that can't be.","start":2168.776,"stop":2185.882,"duration":17.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How much do you think [Inaudible]","start":2185.882,"stop":2191.991,"duration":6.11}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"In the future?","start":2191.991,"stop":2192.904,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Aggregate.","start":2192.904,"stop":2193.709,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Aggregate depreciation.","start":2193.709,"stop":2194.975,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2194.975,"stop":2198.06,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he's only entitled to aggregate depreciation after you recompute his past taxes, that's about $17 million.","start":2198.06,"stop":2205.714,"duration":7.65},{"text":"The price he would have paid had he bought the ship under the act, right.","start":2205.714,"stop":2210.423,"duration":4.71}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] then the problem isn't about the $26 million that this economic investment.","start":2210.423,"stop":2217.971,"duration":7.55},{"text":"The problem is I suppose that if he has an economic investment of $26 million, how can you say he is entitled to $26 million depreciation?","start":2217.971,"stop":2227.368,"duration":9.4},{"text":"Isn't the fact however, that reason that he only get $17 million from now on in your view rather than $26 million if you thought of the only way you can get the depreciation back on your inner -- on your mutual debits and credits is by doing it this way.","start":2227.368,"stop":2245.772,"duration":18.4},{"text":"I mean, this is the only way the depreciation is returned to you is he took?","start":2245.772,"stop":2249.512,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2249.512,"stop":2250.307,"duration":0.79},{"text":"The way he has -- the fallacy of what he does is that he has made all his computations on the basis that his basis was at the time of the act $47 million, the amount that he paid for the ships.","start":2250.307,"stop":2264.189,"duration":13.88},{"text":"That isn't true because at that time he has taken $11 million in depreciation and his adjustment basis was not $47 million, it was $47 million minus depreciation he took.","start":2264.189,"stop":2273.461,"duration":9.27},{"text":"Now the statute as we point out in the brief and as I shall try to explain more fully tomorrow, the statute in the course of the adjustments makes it quite explicit that he must sign an agreement agreeing to certain tax effects, this is in 9(c)(1) of the statute, One of these tax effects is the dis-allowance of all past depreciation reductions.","start":2273.461,"stop":2294.775,"duration":21.31},{"text":"Now when we disallow those deductions and recompute his taxes, as though they hadn't been allowable, that escalates his basis back up to the amount it was before he took it, that's why you start [Inaudible] then we say you take from the basis the amount of the purchase price differential which is line 3 on page 7, $29 million and you come out with -- and they come out and I would like to emphasize this now, you come out with under our submission, the basis which the taxpayer would have had, had he purchased the ship under the act.","start":2294.775,"stop":2328.934,"duration":34.16},{"text":"Now, there's a very simple way to decide this despite concentrating on that point.","start":2328.934,"stop":2334.152,"duration":5.22},{"text":"The act quite clearly says in the beginning of Section 9, which is the only section which is intimately involved with this case, that the adjustment -- this is on page 11 of our brief, the adjustment shall be made as here and after provided by treating the vessel as if it were being sold to the applicant on the date of the enactment of this Act and not before that time.","start":2334.152,"stop":2356.716,"duration":22.56},{"text":"Now if you apply that alone, you would come out with a government's answer.","start":2356.716,"stop":2360.952,"duration":4.24},{"text":"If you treat this vessel and if it would be sold to the applicant on the date of the enactment to the act and not before, this basis would be the basis he would have in the vessel if he bought the vessel on the date of enactment and the enactment not before, and that basis would have to be the statutory sales rate minus certain minor adjustments.","start":2360.952,"stop":2380.332,"duration":19.38},{"text":"For example, for the trading of ships which aren't important.","start":2380.332,"stop":2383.516,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"$30 million [Inaudible]","start":2383.516,"stop":2384.575,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Approximately sir.","start":2384.575,"stop":2385.472,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You start all over after washing it all out on previous computations to start depreciation with now the statutory [Inaudible], is that it?","start":2385.472,"stop":2392.848,"duration":7.38}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, that's the only depreciation he gets Mr. Justice Brennan, because the past depreciation has been wiped out.","start":2392.848,"stop":2398.126,"duration":5.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And you can't  and somewhere I don't see it but I suppose there is somewhere between your items 4 and 9 I guess, is that where you find [Inaudible]","start":2398.126,"stop":2409.776,"duration":11.65}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"4 and 9 of where?","start":2409.776,"stop":2411.312,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There was [Inaudible] in line 1 and 46.","start":2411.312,"stop":2416.279,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you refer to?","start":2416.279,"stop":2418.284,"duration":2.01},{"text":"The depreciation is washed out by the application of Section 9(c)(1), 9(c)(1) is on 14 and it says in so many words, depreciation and amortization allowed or allowable up to the date of the enactment of this act for Federal tax purposes shall be treated as not having been allowable, that takes care of that and in return for that, his taxes are recomputed and so he hasn't taken it.","start":2418.284,"stop":2441.994,"duration":23.71}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"We're on page 7 -- where on page 7 in the unwinding operations as the government takes back depreciation?","start":2441.994,"stop":2449.104,"duration":7.11}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, it's hidden.","start":2449.104,"stop":2450.929,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's it.","start":2450.929,"stop":2451.979,"duration":1.05},{"text":"Isn't it hidden in one?","start":2451.979,"stop":2453.314,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's hidden in A, refund of taxes on return sure to hire [Inaudible] less taxes--","start":2453.314,"stop":2457.919,"duration":4.61}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless we want the taxes paid.","start":2457.919,"stop":2460.237,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you see if you're going to the unwinding operation Mr. Justice White, is to have him return to the United States the $13 million in charter hire and that's line 4.","start":2460.237,"stop":2470.026,"duration":9.79}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":2470.026,"stop":2470.947,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":2470.947,"stop":2471.436,"duration":0.49},{"text":"Now in connection with the return of that, we can't -- and we recompute his taxes for those years as though that amount wasn't an income, that comes 9 (b) (a).","start":2471.436,"stop":2481.905,"duration":10.47},{"text":"Well, we couldn't just do that in enacting the statute because then he might have a loss for that.","start":2481.905,"stop":2486.528,"duration":4.62},{"text":"He would have taken this enormous depreciation.","start":2486.528,"stop":2488.845,"duration":2.32},{"text":"We're going to take a large item out of income, he would have a loss which you could carry over to other years?","start":2488.845,"stop":2492.519,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What line is that?","start":2492.519,"stop":2494.864,"duration":2.35},{"text":"Line 8, a brief of the tax if actually paid [Inaudible]","start":2494.864,"stop":2500.98,"duration":6.12}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the refund is the end result of the re-computation.","start":2500.98,"stop":2505.689,"duration":4.71},{"text":"Perhaps the language in that line could be more explicit.","start":2505.689,"stop":2510.353,"duration":4.66},{"text":"What I mean by it now and what I would like you to treat it as meaning is the refund after the re-computation.","start":2510.353,"stop":2516.149,"duration":5.8}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The basis is returned in line 1, otherwise we start with the lower basis?","start":2516.149,"stop":2527.03,"duration":10.88}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Line one is just the original purchase.","start":2527.03,"stop":2528.822,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly, but as of the time you started the computation the basis is actually lower than that.","start":2528.822,"stop":2537.266,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's true.","start":2537.266,"stop":2538.123,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And so, you're taking the basis back.","start":2538.123,"stop":2540.425,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Right and we take the basis back.","start":2540.425,"stop":2541.582,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"On line one.","start":2541.582,"stop":2543.702,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Wherever you like.","start":2543.702,"stop":2544.49,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible][Laughter]","start":2544.49,"stop":2547.317,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Coming back to the argument, I was making on the basis of the injunction in the act to treat the taxpayer as though he had bought the vessel after the enactment of the act, if you take that literally and if you apply it and if you apply to tax purposes, obviously the basis you would have is the basis you would have had if he bought the ship under the act and the basis would be essentially the statutory sales price.","start":2547.317,"stop":2570.731,"duration":23.41},{"text":"Now that's very important, because if his basis is higher than that in the years after the statute and he has a competitive advantage over people who bought the ships under the act.","start":2570.731,"stop":2581.473,"duration":10.74},{"text":"They would have bought a ship at the statutory price and they would only get depreciation based on the statutory price.","start":2581.473,"stop":2589.09,"duration":7.62},{"text":"Petitioner argues that he bought the ship beforehand would be in the same kind of ship would be entitled to depreciation on a much higher basis, in this case about $9 million higher.","start":2589.09,"stop":2599,"duration":9.91},{"text":"That would mean that if he earned a certain amount of gross income each year, he would have a lower amount of taxable income because he takes the larger depreciation and that would mean comparing him with his competitors on the same amount of gross income, he would have larger after tax then which would be an unfair competitive advantage and it's quite clear that the general purpose of the statute is inconsistent with that.","start":2599,"stop":2619.932,"duration":20.93},{"text":"The legislative history which we cite and which petitioner relies on, it says over and over again that the purpose is to put him in the same boat as other people who bought these ships.","start":2619.932,"stop":2631.711,"duration":11.78},{"text":"Now under the petitioner's argument, you can't do that.","start":2631.711,"stop":2634.803,"duration":3.09},{"text":"Well, what I would like to argue in a constructive fashion rather than the destructive fashion tomorrow is that petitioner -- the reason why the basis in this case is different from the original purchase price of $47 million minus the net return $20 million, is that it isn't like the case Mr. Justice Goldberg gave during petitioner's argument.","start":2634.803,"stop":2661.991,"duration":27.19},{"text":"If you bought something for $100 and got $20 back ordinarily your basis would be $80, but in that situation no tax effects are connected with the return of the $20.","start":2661.991,"stop":2672.35,"duration":10.36},{"text":"What I should like to demonstrate to you tomorrow is that there's an entirely different result if tax effect, income tax effects are connected with the return of the $20.","start":2672.35,"stop":2682.74,"duration":10.39},{"text":"It's possible if all that $20 for example was taken into income by the buyer that it wouldn't have any effect on this basis.","start":2682.74,"stop":2691.712,"duration":8.97},{"text":"On the other hand, certain income tax deductions are associated whether you would have a different effect.","start":2691.712,"stop":2696.332,"duration":4.62},{"text":"Therefore, our argument our constructive argument rests on the premise if there are taxes effects connected with the statute and that by applying the tax effects, you come out with the statutory sales price.","start":2696.332,"stop":2706.455,"duration":10.12},{"text":"I think it would be better if I start with that tomorrow fresh from our show, if I may, I will stop now.","start":2706.455,"stop":2714.332,"duration":7.88}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 27, 1965","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren11/oral_argument_audio/14478","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bender, you may continue your argument.","start":0,"stop":4.913,"duration":4.91}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":4.913,"stop":7.181,"duration":2.27},{"text":"Yesterday, I tried to show how petitioners argument in this case was wrong in two respects, first of all, by giving to applicants readjustment under the 1946 statute, a higher basis for income tax purposes, then a purchaser would have had under the statute.","start":7.181,"stop":28,"duration":20.82},{"text":"Petitioner's argument ignores a direction of the statute to treat the vessel and the purchaser and the applicant for adjustment as if the vessel were being sold to the applicant on the date of the enactment of this Act.","start":28,"stop":41.373,"duration":13.37},{"text":"Second of all, I tried to show that petitioner's argument by giving it greater depreciation, then its economic investment on its own theory of economic investment would give it obviously too much depreciation and an unfair competitive advantage.","start":41.373,"stop":57.842,"duration":16.47},{"text":"I said that today I would try to show how my close application of the provisions of the 1946 Act, you could and should reach the result for which the government contends, name it that the basis to an applicant for adjustment under the 1946 Act is the basis the applicant would have had as a purchaser under the act.","start":57.842,"stop":81.244,"duration":23.4},{"text":"For that purpose, again, I shall have to refer to figures and again I shall try to restrict them to the figures on page 7 in the brief.","start":81.244,"stop":90.471,"duration":9.23},{"text":"Let me first go, recapitulate somewhat what Mr. McConnell did yesterday in giving some of the background of the statute.","start":90.471,"stop":99.76,"duration":9.29},{"text":"As Mr. McConnell said, the 18 vessels connected with this case were bought by the taxpayer between 1942 and 1946 for prices which were quite high reflecting war time cost of the vessels.","start":99.76,"stop":117.298,"duration":17.54},{"text":"The prices paid appear on line one of the schedule on page 7, and that is about $47 million.","start":117.298,"stop":126.001,"duration":8.7},{"text":"The purchase price was paid for these ships in cash and also in mortgages and also in trade-ins of other ships.","start":126.001,"stop":134.374,"duration":8.37},{"text":"I don't think there's any need for us to worry further in the argument about the exact method of payment.","start":134.374,"stop":141.235,"duration":6.86},{"text":"And I think the taxpayer agrees that it doesn't matter in this case whether the payment was made by cash or trade-in or mortgage.","start":141.235,"stop":149.313,"duration":8.08}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You have a figure of 46, maybe a 973?","start":149.313,"stop":153.444,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":153.444,"stop":154.062,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And he has a figure of $49 million 582 on this.","start":154.062,"stop":157.081,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"The difference is the trade-in of ships, ours is exclusive of trade-in that is --","start":157.081,"stop":163.274,"duration":6.19}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Now it's $2 million and 6, I see.","start":163.274,"stop":164.409,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":164.409,"stop":165.034,"duration":0.63},{"text":"If you add those together you get the same figure.","start":165.034,"stop":168.585,"duration":3.55},{"text":"Now during the war, these ships were all charted back to the government under bareboat charters.","start":168.585,"stop":175.164,"duration":6.58},{"text":"The amount of charter hire received was about $13 million, that appears on line 4 of this chart.","start":175.164,"stop":183.543,"duration":8.38},{"text":"Also, as it came out yesterday, during the war while these boats were being charted to the United States, petitioner took depreciation on the vessels in computing its income taxes on this $13 million charter.","start":183.543,"stop":198.592,"duration":15.05},{"text":"The depreciation was about a $11 million, so you have up until the time of the petitioner buying the ships for $47 million, chartering them back to the government for about $13 million.","start":198.592,"stop":209.601,"duration":11.01},{"text":"Taking that $13 million into income for federal income tax purposes, meanwhile, depreciating the boats of federal income tax purposes by total of about $11 million.","start":209.601,"stop":219.995,"duration":10.39},{"text":"So at the time the Act is passed in March 1946, I think it's quite clear that the basis of the ships has been depreciated down from the original cost about $47 million by the amount of depreciation taken about $11 million.","start":219.995,"stop":238.21,"duration":18.22},{"text":"Now comes the 1946 Act.","start":238.21,"stop":241.185,"duration":2.97},{"text":"Again, as Mr. McConnell described yesterday, the purpose of the Act in general was to sell all these ships which the government had acquired during the war to private parties at stable prices called the statutory sales price.","start":241.185,"stop":255.468,"duration":14.28},{"text":"These prices were roughly in the case of cargo vessels which are involved in this case, about half what those vessels had cost people during the war.","start":255.468,"stop":265.313,"duration":9.84},{"text":"Anyone could buy one, speaking in general.","start":265.313,"stop":268.149,"duration":2.84},{"text":"Now, if that is all the Act have done, it would have been a bit unfair to people who had bought ships during the war at double the statutory prices.","start":268.149,"stop":276.609,"duration":8.46},{"text":"So the Act contains a section, Section 9, which provided that persons who had bought vessels during the war could apply for an adjustment.","start":276.609,"stop":286.885,"duration":10.28},{"text":"And the problem here is the effect of that adjustment which petitioner applied for and received upon petitioner's basis for income tax purposes.","start":286.885,"stop":295.458,"duration":8.57},{"text":"Let me try if I may to summarize for you, the nature of this Section 9 adjustment.","start":295.458,"stop":302.969,"duration":7.51},{"text":"The provision to Section 9 seemed enormously complicated.","start":302.969,"stop":306.159,"duration":3.19},{"text":"There are eight subsections and then there's also subsection 9(b) and there is also Subsection C, but it's not as complicated as it seems on the face of it.","start":306.159,"stop":315.607,"duration":9.45},{"text":"Essentially, there are three parts to the adjustment.","start":315.607,"stop":319.843,"duration":4.24},{"text":"The overriding purpose of the whole thing is as I said before, to put the purchaser in the position he would have been at if he bought the ships under the Act.","start":319.843,"stop":329.978,"duration":10.13},{"text":"Therefore, the first part of the adjustment which is contained in subsections 9(b) 1 through 4.","start":329.978,"stop":338.354,"duration":8.38},{"text":"Those are on the pages 11a and 12a of the appendix to our brief and to some extent in 9(b) 7, provides that a credit shall be given to the applicant for the difference between the price he paid during the war and the statutory sales price, in this case that amount was $29,287,000, that's line 3 on page 7.","start":338.354,"stop":363.59,"duration":25.24},{"text":"That gives him back the difference between the high price he paid in the statutory sales price.","start":363.59,"stop":368.989,"duration":5.4},{"text":"But that alone, excuse me, I like to emphasize now that this -- for that chambers, for that credit in the statute, no income tax consequences are provided.","start":368.989,"stop":381.276,"duration":12.29},{"text":"It simply provides that a credit shall be given for the difference in price.","start":381.276,"stop":385.28,"duration":4},{"text":"No, that payment to the applicant is not a taxable payment.","start":385.28,"stop":390.786,"duration":5.51},{"text":"That alone however, would not put the applicant in the position he would have been in had he bought the ship after the Act because he had used the ship during the war.","start":390.786,"stop":401.761,"duration":10.98},{"text":"He had charted it to the government and received $13 million in charter hire and in fact he paid income taxes on that amount.","start":401.761,"stop":407.985,"duration":6.22},{"text":"So the second part of this adjustment is an unwinding of the transactions which the applicant actually entered into with the ship during the war.","start":407.985,"stop":418.355,"duration":10.37},{"text":"Now that part is contained in subsections 9(b) 6 and to some extent in 9(b) 8.","start":418.355,"stop":427.098,"duration":8.74},{"text":"What the Act provides is that all the charter hire, which the applicant received from the United States during the war should be returned to the United States.","start":427.098,"stop":435.805,"duration":8.71},{"text":"Now in -- since the applicant had paid income taxes on that amount in return for that, those amounts are treated as if they had never been received in income and the applicant's income taxes are recomputed as though those amounts had never been received in income that's provided in 9(b) 8 by applying the provisions of 9(c) 1. 9(c) 1 is quite explicit on that amounts credited to the Secretary under the Section 9(b) 6, that is for charter hire, shall be treated for Federal Tax purposes as not having been received but accrued as income.","start":435.805,"stop":474.5,"duration":38.69},{"text":"That alone however, still wouldn't have been enough because the applicant was taking depreciation deductions on these ships and if you just took the amount out of income, he would have these enormous deductions, $11 million, but no income to offset them.","start":474.5,"stop":488.123,"duration":13.62},{"text":"So he either have -- it would either be offset of other income which he had for which he wouldn't be entitled to the deductions or he have a loss which he would carry over to other years.","start":488.123,"stop":497.231,"duration":9.11},{"text":"So is it part of the total unwinding, we have to take away those depreciation deductions also and that's provided in 9(c) 1, depreciation amortization allowed or allowable for Federal Tax purposes shall be treated as not having been allowed.","start":497.231,"stop":511.915,"duration":14.68},{"text":"Well that's then the second part of the adjustment.","start":511.915,"stop":514.116,"duration":2.2},{"text":"You give back the charter hire and you recompute the taxes as though the charter hire had never been received and as though depreciation deductions had not been allowable.","start":514.116,"stop":523.476,"duration":9.36},{"text":"Now notice that there, Federal Tax consequences are very clearly provided in the Act for the giving back of charter hire, there is a corresponding lowering of federal income taxes.","start":523.476,"stop":537.219,"duration":13.74},{"text":"You take that amount out of income and you re-compute the taxes as though that amount had never been paid as income, even though it had in fact been paid.","start":537.219,"stop":545.309,"duration":8.09},{"text":"Essentially, it amounts to a deduction from federal income taxes for the years in which the charter hire has been received.","start":545.309,"stop":552.707,"duration":7.4},{"text":"Now, even those two things alone do not completely put the applicant in the position he would have been in, had he not bought the vessels until the date of the Act.","start":552.707,"stop":561.75,"duration":9.04},{"text":"Because, if he hadn't bought the vessels, he wouldn't have traded in vessels, in this case the applicant traded in 4 vessels and those vessels, he would have charted to the government by trading them and he didn't.","start":561.75,"stop":572.976,"duration":11.23},{"text":"Also in buying the vessels he made quite a substantial economic investment.","start":572.976,"stop":577.049,"duration":4.07},{"text":"If he hadn't made that economic investment, he would have invested the money some place else or put it in the bank and receive some income on it.","start":577.049,"stop":583.583,"duration":6.53},{"text":"So the third part of the adjustment which the Act provides, is to give him the income he would have received during the war if he hadn't purchased the ships until the date of the Act, and that's provided in 9(b) 5 and 9(b) 6.","start":583.583,"stop":599.361,"duration":15.78},{"text":"One, we give him the charter hire which he would have received on the ships traded in.","start":599.361,"stop":604.57,"duration":5.21},{"text":"Two, we gave him interest at the rate of 3.5% on the economic investment he made in the ships.","start":604.57,"stop":612.352,"duration":7.78},{"text":"Again, corresponding to that payment to him which would have been ordinary income if it had been paid during the war, we impose federal income taxes on that.","start":612.352,"stop":621.863,"duration":9.51},{"text":"Again, that's provided in 9(c) 1, amounts credited to the applicant under subsections (b) 5 and (b) 6 shall be treated for Federal Tax purposes as having been received and accrued as income in the taxable year which was on the date of the enactment of this Act.","start":621.863,"stop":639.401,"duration":17.54},{"text":"So, these amounts are credited to him and income taxes are imposed upon the applicant in the year 1946.","start":639.401,"stop":648.442,"duration":9.04},{"text":"Those three things together, you give him back the difference in purchase price, you impose no tax consequences on that.","start":648.442,"stop":654.986,"duration":6.54},{"text":"He gives you back the charter hire, you give them back the income taxes you paid on the receipt of the charter hire and we give him income he would have received if he hadn't purchased the ships an imposed taxes on that amount essentially, not completely, not exactly but essentially put the applicant in the position he would have been had he not purchased the ships until the date of the Act.","start":654.986,"stop":675.188,"duration":20.2}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bender, where in your chart on page 7 does he give back the depreciation?","start":675.188,"stop":682.052,"duration":6.86}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he doesn't give back the depreciation.","start":682.052,"stop":686.89,"duration":4.84},{"text":"We take out of his income for the years in which he received charter hire, the charter hire he received.","start":686.89,"stop":693.815,"duration":6.93},{"text":"We also disallow for those years as deductions, the depreciation, the sum -- then we re-compute his taxes.","start":693.815,"stop":698.415,"duration":4.6},{"text":"The sum of that re-computation is in line A, $430,206 that's a --","start":698.415,"stop":707.75,"duration":9.34}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":707.75,"stop":712.965,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"The precise figures do not appear in the record.","start":712.965,"stop":716.039,"duration":3.07},{"text":"In the petitioner's appendix, you can find the depreciation figures in Exhibit G in the interim agreement and they add up to as we say in the brief over $11 million, but the precise tax calculations were not put in the record.","start":716.039,"stop":727.79,"duration":11.75},{"text":"The only thing that appears in the record is the sum of the re-computation of taxes for all of these, not only the giving back of the charter hire but also the substituted charter hire and that's --","start":727.79,"stop":738.226,"duration":10.44}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":738.226,"stop":742.523,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes, yes.","start":742.523,"stop":745.208,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":745.208,"stop":750.822,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, right.","start":750.822,"stop":753.442,"duration":2.62},{"text":"Now, the essence of our argument is that because of the tax consequences provided for the second and third parts of the adjustment I've described, that is the imposition of income tax on the charter hire an interest credited to the applicant and the forgiveness of income tax on the charter hire which the applicant pays back to the United States, because of these tax consequences, those parts of the adjustment have no effect upon basis.","start":753.442,"stop":785.174,"duration":31.73},{"text":"Essentially, we argue that an amount paid by a buyer to a seller on which he takes a deduction from income, for Federal Tax purposes doesn't affect his basis.","start":785.174,"stop":798.285,"duration":13.11},{"text":"On the other hand, an amount paid by a seller to a buyer which is taken into income by the applicant -- by the buyer doesn't affect his basis.","start":798.285,"stop":807.269,"duration":8.98},{"text":"That means that the only part of this adjustment which affects basis is the purchase price credit, the $29 million.","start":807.269,"stop":815.222,"duration":7.95},{"text":"And that is the amount of that credit diminishes basis from the original price which is $49 -- $47 million by the $29 million and you come out -- now this figures on page 8, if you make that subtraction, you come out with $17,800,000 which is the basis the applicant would have had if he bought the ship under the Act.","start":815.222,"stop":836.474,"duration":21.25},{"text":"Now I'd like to try to demonstrate to you with some simple examples, not in the context of this rather complicated case why it is true that amounts which the buyer pays to the seller and which the buyer deducts from income do not affect his basis.","start":836.474,"stop":854.631,"duration":18.16},{"text":"And on the other hand, amounts which the seller pays to the buyer which the buyer includes an income do not affect his basis leaving in this case only the amount of the purchase price adjustment which has no income tax consequences under the statute.","start":854.631,"stop":867.725,"duration":13.09},{"text":"Take for an example, a very simple case.","start":867.725,"stop":872.785,"duration":5.06},{"text":"I'll use figures of hundreds of dollars rather than millions of dollars but the figures are inappropriate.","start":872.785,"stop":878.081,"duration":5.3},{"text":"Suppose a buyer buys a building, a business building for a $100 and as part of the buying agreement, as part of the contract, he agrees to rent it back to the seller for one year for $10.","start":878.081,"stop":893.866,"duration":15.78},{"text":"Now, the total amount the buyer then -- and the agreement also provides that the $10 rent shall be payable in advance at the time of the agreement.","start":893.866,"stop":903.167,"duration":9.3},{"text":"Now the total amount the buyer is going to pay in cash is $90, $100 for the building less $10 rent coming back.","start":903.167,"stop":912.6,"duration":9.43},{"text":"However, I think it's quite clear that if the $10 rental payment is included in the buyer's income for income tax purposes, his basis in the building isn't $90, his basis is a $100.","start":912.6,"stop":925.447,"duration":12.85},{"text":"Essentially, the basis is the amount he paid for the building, a $100.","start":925.447,"stop":929.631,"duration":4.18},{"text":"The $10 payment which comes back, and which is set off against the $100 payment, doesn't affect his basis because it goes into his income.","start":929.631,"stop":938.086,"duration":8.46},{"text":"And it has to be that way because if that went on for 10 years and his basis was only $90, he would have taken into income a total of a hundred dollars, $10 each year.","start":938.086,"stop":949.853,"duration":11.77},{"text":"But only gotten depreciation deductions of $90 and that wouldn't be right since he didn't have any net -- he clearly didn't have any net gain.","start":949.853,"stop":957.45,"duration":7.6},{"text":"So, I think that shows in a rather simple form, that an amount which the buyer takes into income which is offset against the amount he pays doesn't affect his basis.","start":957.45,"stop":968.235,"duration":10.78},{"text":"On the other hand, an amount he pays which he deducts does not affect his basis, take same situation of buying a building and suppose that here the agreement obligates the buyer to invest $10 in advertising, his supposed part of a real estate development and he must invest $10 in addition to the hundred dollars in the first year in advertising the building or his services and suppose even then he has to pay the $10 to the seller who's an advertising agency, and suppose that the $10 is deductible from ordinary income, as I suppose it would be.","start":968.235,"stop":1003.019,"duration":34.78},{"text":"Again, he pays here a $110 but his basis isn't $110, his basis is only a hundred dollars.","start":1003.019,"stop":1009.65,"duration":6.63},{"text":"The only part of the payment which is capital is the $100, the $10 is deducted from ordinary income.","start":1009.65,"stop":1015.597,"duration":5.95},{"text":"The $10 doesn't go into the basis computation, that has to be true because if the $10 did go into the basis computation, he get a total of $120 deductions for only $110 outlay.","start":1015.597,"stop":1027.731,"duration":12.13},{"text":"The outlay is a 110, if he got a deduction which he did from ordinary incomes of paying $10 and if his basis was a 110, then he gets depreciation deductions of a 110 plus the 10 he has already got, and which would be a 120 for a total payment of a 110 which would be wrong.","start":1027.731,"stop":1045.126,"duration":17.39},{"text":"So amounts which come in, which he takes into income don't affect basis.","start":1045.126,"stop":1051.097,"duration":5.97},{"text":"Amounts which he pays, which he deducts from income don't affect basis.","start":1051.097,"stop":1055.278,"duration":4.18},{"text":"Now those examples are quite close to this case.","start":1055.278,"stop":1059.443,"duration":4.16},{"text":"The only difference between those and this case is that in this case, you have those payments accompanying a purchase price adjustment.","start":1059.443,"stop":1068.389,"duration":8.95},{"text":"But we can make the example just a little bit more complicated and put that in and then I think you'll have this precise case.","start":1068.389,"stop":1075.045,"duration":6.66},{"text":"Suppose again, he buys the building for a $100.","start":1075.045,"stop":1078.469,"duration":3.42},{"text":"Suppose now that a year or so goes by and the seller says to him, You paid too much for the building.","start":1078.469,"stop":1086.743,"duration":8.27},{"text":"The seller wants to give him a refund because of some ongoing commercial relationship they have.","start":1086.743,"stop":1091.814,"duration":5.07},{"text":"I will give you back, the seller says, $50 of what you pay.","start":1091.814,"stop":1097.38,"duration":5.57},{"text":"Now that were all if you just gave him back the $50, his basis would go down by $50, But suppose as a condition of giving back, first he says, I'll give you back the $50 if you will rent the building to me for 10 years and the rental is payable -- I will pay you the rental at the time of the refund in advance -- rent the building for one year I suppose, $10 a year.","start":1097.38,"stop":1122.275,"duration":24.89},{"text":"So how much does the seller pay the buyer back, $60, $50 is the purchase price adjustment, $10 is the advance rental payment.","start":1122.275,"stop":1132.396,"duration":10.12},{"text":"But the basis of the buyer is reduced not by $60, only by $50 if that $10 rental payment is taken into income just as in the past example.","start":1132.396,"stop":1142.575,"duration":10.18},{"text":"Now that's just like the part of this case which involves the re -- the substituted charter hire and 3.5% interest.","start":1142.575,"stop":1151.512,"duration":8.94},{"text":"That's just what happening in that part of this case.","start":1151.512,"stop":1154.702,"duration":3.19},{"text":"The government is giving back the purchase price adjustment, difference between the price originally paid and the statutory sales price and it's also paying to the buyer some income namely, substituted charter hire and the ships traded-in and 3.5% interest which by the very terms of the statute is taken into income for income tax purposes in the year 1946 and he couldn't' provide that any clear.","start":1154.702,"stop":1181.069,"duration":26.37},{"text":"Now, if that were all they were in the statute, just the purchase price adjustment and the return of -- and the payment of substituted charter hire, the basis would be lowered not by the whole amount in this case the $29 million plus the $2,600,000 on line 7, which -- and the $1 million on line 6 which is the substituted charter hire and interest, those amounts wouldn't reduce the basis because those amounts had taken into income for income tax purposes by the taxpayer, the basis would be reduced only by the $20 million.","start":1181.069,"stop":1215.978,"duration":34.91},{"text":"That's half of this case.","start":1215.978,"stop":1217.608,"duration":1.63},{"text":"Therefore, we submit that those amounts in line 6 and 7 substituted charter hire and a 3.5% interest do not affect the basis.","start":1217.608,"stop":1226.839,"duration":9.23},{"text":"The other half of this case is like the following example, which is like when I gave before.","start":1226.839,"stop":1232.625,"duration":5.79},{"text":"You have the same building, same hundred dollars, the same two-year later seller who decides that he has paid too much and wants to give him back $50.","start":1232.625,"stop":1239.805,"duration":7.18},{"text":"But this time as part of the agreement, that he'll only give him back the $50 if the buyer will agree to invest -- let's say $10 in advertising which he has to pay to the seller who is an advertising agency.","start":1239.805,"stop":1254.991,"duration":15.19},{"text":"And let's suppose that it's true that that $10 is deductible from ordinary income by the buyer.","start":1254.991,"stop":1260.774,"duration":5.78},{"text":"Now if that's all you have, what's -- the net payment is 50 minus 10, so it's only 40, but the basis isn't reduced by 40.","start":1260.774,"stop":1269.647,"duration":8.87},{"text":"The basis is reduced by 50.","start":1269.647,"stop":1271.457,"duration":1.81},{"text":"The basis is reduced by the part of the payment which represents the return of capital by the difference between original price and the new price.","start":1271.457,"stop":1279.283,"duration":7.83},{"text":"The $10 payment for advertising which is deductible from ordinary income, doesn't affect the basis for the reason I gave before.","start":1279.283,"stop":1286.531,"duration":7.25},{"text":"If it did, you deduct that amount twice.","start":1286.531,"stop":1289.87,"duration":3.34},{"text":"That's just like the part of this case which involves the payment of charter hire by the applicant back to the United States.","start":1289.87,"stop":1298.771,"duration":8.9},{"text":"That payment is a condition of receiving the adjustment.","start":1298.771,"stop":1303.021,"duration":4.25},{"text":"The adjustment comes to him, he must pay the charter hire back.","start":1303.021,"stop":1307.877,"duration":4.86},{"text":"For the payment of the adjustment to the applicant, there are no income tax consequences imposed.","start":1307.877,"stop":1313.409,"duration":5.53},{"text":"But, for the payment of the charter hire back to the government, there are income tax consequences.","start":1313.409,"stop":1319.347,"duration":5.94},{"text":"Essentially, that amount is taken out of the applicant's income for the years when it was received.","start":1319.347,"stop":1325.201,"duration":5.85},{"text":"It amounts to precisely a deduction from ordinary income for that amount of $13 million, it's a deductible payment.","start":1325.201,"stop":1333.08,"duration":7.88},{"text":"Well, a deductible payment is I think I have demonstrated before, does not affect the basis.","start":1333.08,"stop":1337.725,"duration":4.64},{"text":"Therefore, that amount of charter hire which is paid back to the government under Section 9(b) 6 of the Act, on which federal income taxes are forgiven because of the effect of 9(c) 1 of the Act, doesn't affect the basis.","start":1337.725,"stop":1354.655,"duration":16.93},{"text":"So the basis you come out with here, is simply the amount of the purchase price adjustment which is paid back the first part of the adjustment I described, which doesn't affect -- which doesn't have any federal income tax consequences.","start":1354.655,"stop":1368.374,"duration":13.72},{"text":"The only -- it seems to me that the only ground on which you can dispute that analysis is by saying, as petitioner does say, that in fact federal income tax consequences are not imposed upon these payments in parts two and three of the adjustment.","start":1368.374,"stop":1386.124,"duration":17.75},{"text":"He says, Federal income tax consequences are not imposed on the payment of substituted charter hire income, not imposed on the payment of the 3.5% interest and on the other hand, deductions are not given for the payment of charter hire back to the government.","start":1386.124,"stop":1400.029,"duration":13.9},{"text":"Now if that were true, petitioner would be right, but it just isn't so.","start":1400.029,"stop":1403.805,"duration":3.78},{"text":"And it isn't so because the Act provide as clearly as it could possibly provide the federal income tax consequences are imposed on those payments, and that as I say is provided in 9(b) 8 and 9(c) 1. 9(c) compels an applicant for adjustment as a means of getting the adjustment to sign an agreement, binding upon the Act in any affiliated interest and the agreement is in three parts.","start":1403.805,"stop":1429.577,"duration":25.77},{"text":"One, he's got to agree that depreciation and amortization already taken shall not be treated as allowable for Federal Tax purposes.","start":1429.577,"stop":1437.794,"duration":8.22},{"text":"Two, amounts credit to the Secretary that charter hire he pays shall be treated for federal income tax purposes as not having been received, that is, he gets a deduction for them in the re-computation of taxes.","start":1437.794,"stop":1449.911,"duration":12.12},{"text":"Three, amounts he gets on the 95 and 6, the substituted charter hire interest payments are treated as income for federal income tax purposes in the taxable year of the enactment of the Act, 1946.","start":1449.911,"stop":1461.979,"duration":12.07},{"text":"Then after he signs that agreement, Section 9(b) 8 provides that, they shall be subtracted from the credits in favor of the Secretary the amount of any over payments of Federal Taxes of the applicant resulting from that agreement.","start":1461.979,"stop":1475.349,"duration":13.37},{"text":"And I don't see how that could be any clear that if he has overpaid taxes because he paid taxes on the charter hire which you shouldn't pay and he gets the taxes back, those amounts shall be treated as credits and also any deficiencies in the next sentence shall be treated as credits and their deficiencies in Federal income tax of -- deficiencies in Federal income tax.","start":1475.349,"stop":1499.19,"duration":23.84},{"text":"Then when you come to the end of Subsection 9(b) 8, provides that upon such payment by the Secretary, such overpayment shall be treated as having been refunded and such deficiencies as having been paid.","start":1499.19,"stop":1510.475,"duration":11.28},{"text":"Again, it clearly emphasizes that the effect of this statute is to re-compute the income taxes and to treat any deficiencies or over payments resulting from the re-computation as paid, satisfied, obligation finished, taxes have been recomputed.","start":1510.475,"stop":1527.538,"duration":17.06},{"text":"Well, if  as I tried to show, if you re-compute the taxes in that manner, the only part of this adjustment which can possibly affect basis is the part of this adjustment upon which no Federal Taxes are imposed and that is the difference to credit in Subsections 9(b) 1 through Subsection 9(b) 4, the credit for the difference between the price actually paid by the applicant and the statutory price.","start":1527.538,"stop":1553.466,"duration":25.93},{"text":"And is --","start":1553.466,"stop":1553.679,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bender, are these examples and what you've been saying that really help us in trying to understand why -- well first, do you agree that the investment here was $26 million?","start":1553.679,"stop":1573.413,"duration":19.73}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1573.413,"stop":1575.619,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"By the time that he's paid cash in the past, cash down and he made payments on the mortgage and he still has a part of the mortgage to pay or by the time he gets through paying the mortgage and you add that to his cash payments and his down payments, trade-ins, will it be 26 million or more?","start":1575.619,"stop":1592.388,"duration":16.77}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"No, his investment is not $26 million because $8 million of that $26 million was deducted from his income for Federal Tax purposes and amounts which you deduct from your income for Federal Tax purposes can't possibly constitute investment, for Federal Tax purposes.","start":1592.388,"stop":1607.262,"duration":14.87}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"All I want to know that is what want to ask, I asked whether or not the money he pays to the government will total $26 million or whether it won't -- whether it will or it won't?","start":1607.262,"stop":1616.571,"duration":9.31}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"The money he pays?","start":1616.571,"stop":1617.666,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"On the purchase price.","start":1617.666,"stop":1622.97,"duration":5.3},{"text":"The cash he has paid at the outset, the trade-ins, the payments on the mortgage and the balance due on the mortgage as of now, by the time he has paid the mortgage off, will all of his payments over to the government will be $26 million?","start":1622.97,"stop":1635.695,"duration":12.72}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he originally paid 47 and if you view it that way, that he originally paid 47 and only got back 20 -- 46 only, he got back 20, it would, but that doesn't take into account the $13 million that he got during the --","start":1635.695,"stop":1650.888,"duration":15.19}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I understand that, but -- will he pay over $26 million?","start":1650.888,"stop":1654.323,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"No, he won't because he has received $13 million in charter hire from the government during the war.","start":1654.323,"stop":1659.298,"duration":4.97},{"text":"If you're just going to look at net cash payments Mr. Justice White, you have to take into account the net cash payment of $13 million.","start":1659.298,"stop":1665.222,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well how about the net cash payments on the purchase price?","start":1665.222,"stop":1667.99,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's give him the $46 million.","start":1667.99,"stop":1671.077,"duration":3.09},{"text":"Let's suppose he has paid that all in cash.","start":1671.077,"stop":1673.424,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1673.424,"stop":1673.855,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Now during the war, the government paid him $13 million and after the war, when he applies for an adjustment, he pays the government back $20 million, I mean the government pays him back $20 million.","start":1673.855,"stop":1684.577,"duration":10.72},{"text":"So the government has paid him a total of $13 million plus $20 million.","start":1684.577,"stop":1687.769,"duration":3.19},{"text":"He's paid the government a total of $46 million.","start":1687.769,"stop":1690.946,"duration":3.18},{"text":"If you're going to look at how much cash he's paid, you take $46 million and deduct the total amount the government's paid him, namely $13 million --","start":1690.946,"stop":1696.665,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"No -- let's set aside what you said was  he had income tax consequences.","start":1696.665,"stop":1703.316,"duration":6.65},{"text":"I was going to put aside the charter hire payments?","start":1703.316,"stop":1706.187,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Well but after the adjustment is paid, the charter hire payments haven't had income tax consequences anymore because the taxes have been forgiven on those amounts.","start":1706.187,"stop":1717.195,"duration":11.01}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Actually what you're saying is that they've paid on $26 million, a sum that was paid in the form of interest, charter hire and so on, and not as part of the investment, isn't that what you're saying?","start":1717.195,"stop":1729.923,"duration":12.73}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't -- when you say, it paid out $26 million, I don't know quite what figure you have referenced to it.","start":1729.923,"stop":1734.909,"duration":4.99},{"text":"If you're just going to look at the cash which pass between the government and the taxpayer, they didn't pay the government 26 million --","start":1734.909,"stop":1741.289,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Because they have some offsetting amounts.","start":1741.289,"stop":1743.242,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the $13 million came back there.","start":1743.242,"stop":1744.989,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1744.989,"stop":1746.067,"duration":1.08},{"text":"But of course, the $13 million is now being cashed back.","start":1746.067,"stop":1748.693,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's not being given back.","start":1748.693,"stop":1750.304,"duration":1.61},{"text":"They only gave back 20 million, and they've given -- if the 13 -- if they got the $13 million, then they get another $20 million.","start":1750.304,"stop":1757.184,"duration":6.88},{"text":"The $13 million is not coming back, they're simply getting $20 million rather than a larger amount they would have gotten if the $13 million hasn't been paid back.","start":1757.184,"stop":1764.28,"duration":7.1},{"text":"If you're going to forget about the original payment of $13 million, you're taking that into account twice.","start":1764.28,"stop":1769.086,"duration":4.81}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your other argument, your alternate argument that you are making?","start":1769.086,"stop":1772.788,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes essentially, but I want to emphasize that if you just look at the cash paid by the taxpayer in this case, it does not amount to $26 million, it amounts to considerably less than that.","start":1772.788,"stop":1782.393,"duration":9.61}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] the appellant should prevail in this case on his theory, what preference would he have or what benefits would he have over and above, those that were acquired by someone who bought the same ships under the Act?","start":1782.393,"stop":1805.04,"duration":22.65}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"He would have a higher tax basis than those people.","start":1805.04,"stop":1809.219,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1809.219,"stop":1810.057,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Paul Bender","textObjs":[{"text":"That would mean that each year, he could take a larger deduction from his income for Federal Tax purposes than those people.","start":1810.057,"stop":1818.271,"duration":8.21},{"text":"Therefore, if they each received the same amount of gross income, $10 million let's say, and if he was able to take a $2 million deduction but they only a $1 million deduction.","start":1818.271,"stop":1827.804,"duration":9.53},{"text":"Those deductions don't represent any payment, they simply represent the amortization.","start":1827.804,"stop":1831.798,"duration":3.99},{"text":"He would have a lower taxable income than his competitors on exactly the same gross income and that would give him a competitive advantage, lower taxable income means a higher after tax income.","start":1831.798,"stop":1844.081,"duration":12.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":1844.081,"stop":1846.239,"duration":2.16},{"text":"Mr. McConnell?","start":1846.239,"stop":1848.827,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":1848.827,"stop":1851.85,"duration":3.02},{"text":"I have a very short time remaining here that I would like to answer some of the questions that were raised and I think if we're coming back now to the point at which this should have begun and on which it shall be decided.","start":1851.85,"stop":1867.341,"duration":15.49},{"text":"And that is, Mr. Justice White's question of how much did this taxpayer pay for these vessels.","start":1867.341,"stop":1874.478,"duration":7.14},{"text":"Now Mr. Bender says, we didn't pay $26 million, but it's stipulated, it's in the record.","start":1874.478,"stop":1880.664,"duration":6.19},{"text":"It's clear we paid $16 million before any adjustment.","start":1880.664,"stop":1885.254,"duration":4.59},{"text":"It is clear that after the adjustment, we owed $10 million more dollars which we have paid, making a total of $26 million which regardless of how it was computed is the purchase price of these 18 vessels and therefore, the economic investment.","start":1885.254,"stop":1903.499,"duration":18.25},{"text":"Now, there have been several questions asked about the purpose of this of getting back statutory sales price, Mr. Chief Justice asked this yesterday.","start":1903.499,"stop":1911.901,"duration":8.4},{"text":"If you'll look at the comparison of the bills that we have in our Appendix C, showing the bills considered and rejected and the bill adopted, you will see that one of the bills said, Reduce it down to the statutory sales price, that's not the bill adopted.","start":1911.901,"stop":1929.787,"duration":17.89},{"text":"That's the computation you would get from Schedule 1 on page 7 if that bill had been adopted.","start":1929.787,"stop":1936.042,"duration":6.25},{"text":"However, it was recognized everywhere that the adjustment would not be made down to the statutory sales price and if it was not made to the statutory sales price, therefore, any taxpayer who purchased before and whose price were adjusted would pay more than the statutory sales price.","start":1936.042,"stop":1954.418,"duration":18.38},{"text":"We paid $26 million which is more than statutory sales price.","start":1954.418,"stop":1958.758,"duration":4.34},{"text":"So you do not get it down to the statutory sales price and we submit that Section 9 (b), the application of formula, will not produce this table, Schedule 1 on page 7 nor the results contain therein.","start":1958.758,"stop":1973.127,"duration":14.37},{"text":"And it is true that if you look at this, you will see that the government admits a net payment, and in fact there was no payment, all of this is misleading.","start":1973.127,"stop":1983.139,"duration":10.01},{"text":"If you look at page 7, they talk about charter hire return.","start":1983.139,"stop":1986.788,"duration":3.65},{"text":"No charter hire was returned.","start":1986.788,"stop":1989.405,"duration":2.62},{"text":"The bill rejected --","start":1989.405,"stop":1992.66,"duration":3.26}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't there a lot of points that it wasn't --","start":1992.66,"stop":1994.272,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly Your Honor.","start":1994.272,"stop":1995.339,"duration":1.07},{"text":"Let me go on and say the effect of --","start":1995.339,"stop":1996.624,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think that you might owe the government some charter hire in return of charter hire that you supposed to pay them back for the  and part of its wrapped up in the mortgage?","start":1996.624,"stop":2006.532,"duration":9.91}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it actually wrapped up in the adjustment.","start":2006.532,"stop":2010.046,"duration":3.51},{"text":"These are a series of credits leading to one thing.","start":2010.046,"stop":2013.969,"duration":3.92},{"text":"It's not a division into three adjustments as Mr. Bender stated.","start":2013.969,"stop":2018.474,"duration":4.5},{"text":"You won't find in Section 9(b) anything that will give you lines 1, 2, and 3 on his schedule, it just simply isn't there.","start":2018.474,"stop":2028.125,"duration":9.65},{"text":"In fact, if you look at 9(b) 8, 9(b) 8 says that you must -- there shall be subtracted from the sum of the credits in favor of the commission including the credit in Section 1, where it goes on down by the taxes, it says, If I have to make any such subtractions, the sum of the credits in favor of the applicants exceeds the sum of the credits in favor of the commission, such excess shall be paid by the commission applicant.","start":2028.125,"stop":2055.542,"duration":27.42},{"text":"In other words in sub-paragraph B, you net all of these credits together.","start":2055.542,"stop":2060.599,"duration":5.06},{"text":"Include --","start":2060.599,"stop":2061.241,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You agree, then I suppose that the net credit here of 8(a) is right, $8 million, $8 is right?","start":2061.241,"stop":2067.739,"duration":6.5},{"text":"That you agree --","start":2067.739,"stop":2067.913,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, that's not the net credit that you get on the -- under this section.","start":2067.913,"stop":2070.9,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But you agree with lines 4, 5, 6, 7 and 8?","start":2070.9,"stop":2074.781,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Line 4 is a credit Your Honor that -- now this is not charter hire return, this is a credit for charter hire.","start":2074.781,"stop":2081.358,"duration":6.58}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":2081.358,"stop":2081.58,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Credit should be the word $13 million is right --","start":2081.58,"stop":2084.178,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":2084.178,"stop":2084.893,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- under paragraph 6.","start":2084.893,"stop":2085.927,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2085.927,"stop":2086.511,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Then the credit charter hire on trade-ins --","start":2086.511,"stop":2089.344,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2089.344,"stop":2089.513,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on line 6 --","start":2089.513,"stop":2091.11,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2091.11,"stop":2091.424,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's correct.","start":2091.424,"stop":2092.145,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2092.145,"stop":2092.9,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Interest, on line 7 --","start":2092.9,"stop":2094.529,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2094.529,"stop":2094.764,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's correct.","start":2094.764,"stop":2095.449,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2095.449,"stop":2095.924,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"However, -- and also the 8, although there's no refund again --","start":2095.924,"stop":2100.335,"duration":4.41}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's credit.","start":2100.335,"stop":2100.888,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's debit.","start":2100.888,"stop":2101.918,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":2101.918,"stop":2102.126,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case, it's a debit.","start":2102.126,"stop":2103.341,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And so you must agree then if the net --","start":2103.341,"stop":2105.711,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, because they have overlooked this.","start":2105.711,"stop":2108.433,"duration":2.72},{"text":"There's no place in there for the credit for sub-paragraph 1, where we paid more than the 25% of the statutory sales price.","start":2108.433,"stop":2117.468,"duration":9.03},{"text":"There, we got a credit of sum of $11 million.","start":2117.468,"stop":2121.051,"duration":3.58},{"text":"This is on page 48 of the record Your Honor, stipulated.","start":2121.051,"stop":2124.797,"duration":3.75},{"text":"Now that's under sub-paragraph 1, that's the reason I say, you can't get schedule one from Section 9(b), it's not there.","start":2124.797,"stop":2133.822,"duration":9.03},{"text":"They overlooked a lot --","start":2133.822,"stop":2134.905,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You and the government still seem to be talking about the same factors --","start":2134.905,"stop":2138.679,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We --","start":2138.679,"stop":2138.763,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the same language or even the same transaction.","start":2138.763,"stop":2141.251,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly Your Honor.","start":2141.251,"stop":2142.255,"duration":1},{"text":"Let me just quote this and to get the examples that Mr. Bender gave, under Section 9(c), now we do not say that 9(c) 1 does not have tax effects.","start":2142.255,"stop":2152.722,"duration":10.47},{"text":"We say that the years 42 through 46 were re-computed for the purposes of Section 9(b) 8, part of the formula, that's all, recomputed.","start":2152.722,"stop":2163.644,"duration":10.92},{"text":"In fact, you'll find in the record the effect of this.","start":2163.644,"stop":2167.588,"duration":3.94},{"text":"On page 67, you can see the tax effect of this re-computation.","start":2167.588,"stop":2173.228,"duration":5.64},{"text":"It's a 67 in the record.","start":2173.228,"stop":2176.514,"duration":3.29},{"text":"If you'll look down at line 8, on page 67, this is the sheet that has the total, the last column is the total.","start":2176.514,"stop":2188.799,"duration":12.28},{"text":"Now if you look at this 9(a), it says deduct overpayment of Federal Taxes and in the next line and part of the same line, add deficiencies of Federal Taxes.","start":2188.799,"stop":2196.18,"duration":7.38},{"text":"Now over in the right hand column, overpayment 3.5 million, deficiency $3 million and 90.","start":2196.18,"stop":2203.383,"duration":7.2},{"text":"Now, to get to this depreciation that we've talked so much about, depreciation is not something that comes back in dollars and cents.","start":2203.383,"stop":2211.2,"duration":7.82},{"text":"Depreciation is a deduction allowed by Federal Law on your taxes.","start":2211.2,"stop":2217.415,"duration":6.22},{"text":"Now if you have no income, your depreciation is not going to help you.","start":2217.415,"stop":2221.241,"duration":3.83},{"text":"All the depreciation may do is either reduce your tax or in this case where we treat it as not having been allowed, it increased our tax, we paid more.","start":2221.241,"stop":2232.236,"duration":10.99},{"text":"This item here of deficiency of Federal Taxes, $3 million and 90, is due in part to the fact that we -- this depreciation was treated as not allowable.","start":2232.236,"stop":2245.514,"duration":13.28},{"text":"So that instead of depreciation being in our favor, in which trade is not allowed, our taxes went up and this became a credit.","start":2245.514,"stop":2255.005,"duration":9.49},{"text":"In fact again that's where schedule one is misleading, line 8, that everyone had so much trouble finding on depreciation, it's odd that's the only thing that's not mentioned as having entered in the computation of the taxes.","start":2255.005,"stop":2268.213,"duration":13.21},{"text":"Now, we just say that the government is not being candid in the use of Schedule 1 as to what took place here.","start":2268.213,"stop":2276.677,"duration":8.46},{"text":"One other thing --","start":2276.677,"stop":2277.657,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I take you drew some figures.","start":2277.657,"stop":2280.784,"duration":3.13},{"text":"Do you dispute the fact that you received from the government $20,468,904 plus $13,430,431?","start":2280.784,"stop":2299.356,"duration":18.57}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We certainly do Your Honor, we --","start":2299.356,"stop":2300.846,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Now will you tell me why you dispute that?","start":2300.846,"stop":2303.291,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright sir.","start":2303.291,"stop":2303.507,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Because net payment to the Waterman, $20,468,904.","start":2303.507,"stop":2309.63,"duration":6.12},{"text":"Now item number 10 and then charter hire from the government, $13,430,431.","start":2309.63,"stop":2317.411,"duration":7.78},{"text":"Now, those are two items which as I understood the argument you received, is that wrong?","start":2317.411,"stop":2324.049,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":2324.049,"stop":2324.655,"duration":0.61},{"text":"Your Honor, in fact they claim item 10 as net payment which includes up there, your charter hire return, all of those words are wrong, erroneous, but that includes that above charter hire return.","start":2324.655,"stop":2337.114,"duration":12.46},{"text":"Now let me just explain this though.","start":2337.114,"stop":2339.345,"duration":2.23},{"text":"This is the way that we arrive at it and it goes back to Mr. Justice --","start":2339.345,"stop":2342.072,"duration":2.73}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's equivalent.","start":2342.072,"stop":2343.458,"duration":1.39},{"text":"I understand that, that the re-computing, but I want to now take, forget about all the argument.","start":2343.458,"stop":2349.525,"duration":6.07},{"text":"Let's talk about straight cash in flow, the Waterman, just straight cash. During the period you operated, the charter hire to the government during the war, you received $13,430,431 --","start":2349.525,"stop":2365.751,"duration":16.23}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2365.751,"stop":2366.18,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is that correct?","start":2366.18,"stop":2367.506,"duration":1.33},{"text":"Now after this -- all these adjustments were made, all these adjustments were made, was there a further payment of $20,468,904?","start":2367.506,"stop":2380.402,"duration":12.9}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, there was a reduction in mortgage indebtedness in the amount of $20,554,468.","start":2380.402,"stop":2385.378,"duration":4.98}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, right.","start":2385.378,"stop":2387.649,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, Your Honor though if you'll look at the record in the agreement entered into --","start":2387.649,"stop":2392.484,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now before you leave it, either an actual money received or credit on the mortgage, then you received the benefit of $33,898,904, is that correct?","start":2392.484,"stop":2405.456,"duration":12.97}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, Mr. Justice --","start":2405.456,"stop":2406.528,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well tell me why it isn't correct --","start":2406.528,"stop":2408.177,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Because --","start":2408.177,"stop":2409.633,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I thought you just said, that you got it on a reduction of mortgage indebtedness which is the same as getting it.","start":2409.633,"stop":2415.181,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But Your Honor, the computation or the reduction in mortgage indebtedness took into consideration, that figure was arrived at after taking all of these other credits.","start":2415.181,"stop":2426.086,"duration":10.9}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that, but I'm -- I'm just trying to get the net amount after without the consequences which we have to determine.","start":2426.086,"stop":2435.537,"duration":9.45}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well let me --","start":2435.537,"stop":2437.602,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you in fact receive $13,000,430 and a credit of $20,468,904?","start":2437.602,"stop":2448.647,"duration":11.05}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We received during the war $13 millions of charter hire.","start":2448.647,"stop":2451.524,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":2451.524,"stop":2452.239,"duration":0.72},{"text":"Did you receive a credit on your mortgage indebtedness at $20,468,904?","start":2452.239,"stop":2458.016,"duration":5.78}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right sir.","start":2458.016,"stop":2458.77,"duration":0.75},{"text":"After entering into this agreement.","start":2458.77,"stop":2460.499,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":2460.499,"stop":2461.549,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"By which it stated --","start":2461.549,"stop":2462.859,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2462.859,"stop":2463.068,"duration":0.21},{"text":"Again, I'm not talking --","start":2463.068,"stop":2464.17,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2464.17,"stop":2464.26,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"-- about the consequence, I want to establish the fact.","start":2464.26,"stop":2466.899,"duration":2.64},{"text":"The fact is that Waterman received, in cash and credit $33,898,904, is that correct?","start":2466.899,"stop":2475.158,"duration":8.26}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well yes, and although we had some offsets to this also.","start":2475.158,"stop":2478.72,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but is that a correct fact?","start":2478.72,"stop":2480.712,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We received 13 million in charter hire and 20 million in mortgage adjustment, yes sir.","start":2480.712,"stop":2485.618,"duration":4.91},{"text":"Now, the difference if I may take just a moment in the effect of this 9(c) 1 which was a condition about making this and we entered into an agreement in which 9(c) 1 is a part of the agreement.","start":2485.618,"stop":2497.211,"duration":11.59},{"text":"To get back to the examples of the property purchase, a building for a $100, this is an agreement not between two taxpayers but between the taxing authority, the government and a taxpayer.","start":2497.211,"stop":2510.45,"duration":13.24},{"text":"The taxing authority is the only one then get back and save what depreciation will be allowable, what will not be treated as income, what will be treated had been and received as income?","start":2510.45,"stop":2522.376,"duration":11.93},{"text":"I and another taxpayer cannot agree on that, but the government can and the government entered into an agreement which said, Depreciation and amortization allowed or allowable with respect to the vessel up to the date of enactment of this Act for Federal Tax purposes shall be treated as not having been allowable.","start":2522.376,"stop":2540.238,"duration":17.86},{"text":"Now this is a government, not two taxpayers.","start":2540.238,"stop":2542.661,"duration":2.42},{"text":"So that the government who gives us depreciation or does not give us depreciation said, Alright, we're going to treat it as if you haven't had it.","start":2542.661,"stop":2550.569,"duration":7.91},{"text":"That brought our basis back up, and then it goes on down, Amounts credited, now notice this, credited not returned.","start":2550.569,"stop":2558.507,"duration":7.94},{"text":"Credited to the commission including charter hire shall be treated for Federal Tax purposes as not having been received or accrued as income.","start":2558.507,"stop":2567.532,"duration":9.03},{"text":"Now they didn't say it returned.","start":2567.532,"stop":2569.219,"duration":1.69},{"text":"We don't return it, credited.","start":2569.219,"stop":2572.084,"duration":2.86},{"text":"A credit that enters into the determination of the price adjustment and the government says, We're going to treat that as not having been allowed.","start":2572.084,"stop":2581.984,"duration":9.9},{"text":"Now that gives tax effects in 42 through 46, and the tax effect though then becomes a part of the computation of the adjustment and price under 8.","start":2581.984,"stop":2592.783,"duration":10.8},{"text":"Now therefore we say that this is not the case of where we buy advertising.","start":2592.783,"stop":2597.742,"duration":4.96},{"text":"In fact, if we made a contract with the government in which the government says, You put in $10 of advertising and we'll count it is part of the capital cost then we could do it.","start":2597.742,"stop":2608.563,"duration":10.82},{"text":"The government can agree to that and the government agreed to that in 9(c) 1.","start":2608.563,"stop":2614.059,"duration":5.5},{"text":"This is a contract between a taxpayer and a government who has this taxing authority and therefore, we say that the tax effects are limited solely to those years recomputed.","start":2614.059,"stop":2626.158,"duration":12.1},{"text":"And then though, you don't divide your formula on the 9(b) and the three adjustments that Mr. Bender spoke of.","start":2626.158,"stop":2634.78,"duration":8.62},{"text":"Nowhere will you find, look at the regulation, we ask you, we've set them out in our brief.","start":2634.78,"stop":2639.423,"duration":4.64},{"text":"The regulation promulgated by maritime.","start":2639.423,"stop":2642.874,"duration":3.45},{"text":"If you look at the sub-paragraphs, when they have the credits to the commission and the credits to the applicant, each one of them is stated for the purposes of sub-paragraph 8 and sub-paragraph 8 is where you net this.","start":2642.874,"stop":2656.933,"duration":14.06},{"text":"Now that is one place where the government is correct when they talk about net in line 10, although it's not net payment, but it is net.","start":2656.933,"stop":2666.536,"duration":9.6},{"text":"And if you look at the record of the agreement that was signed by these parties, you will find there, net credit, under sub-paragraph 8 which is part of the formula.","start":2666.536,"stop":2679.403,"duration":12.87},{"text":"You won't find anything about gross price adjustment.","start":2679.403,"stop":2682.869,"duration":3.47},{"text":"You will find that we asked for an adjustment and we still maintain that we are entitled then to all items that -- in that make up that computation of adjustment and by 9(c) 1, these tax effects Mr. Bender says were agreed not to be treated as such tax effect.","start":2682.869,"stop":2703.586,"duration":20.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's suppose that they're making these adjustments on these lines from 4 to 8.","start":2703.586,"stop":2709.607,"duration":6.02},{"text":"Suppose that each of you have just written a check for the -- a separate check for each amount, you would have written the check for the government for 13 million and the government written checks for these other two items -- other three items to use, separate checks, now you just deliver them to each other and consequently, there wouldn't have been any net credit you would already have paid each other off.","start":2709.607,"stop":2733.853,"duration":24.25},{"text":"Now, the economic effect of that I suppose should be the same as this arrangement.","start":2733.853,"stop":2743.633,"duration":9.78}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we say that it --","start":2743.633,"stop":2744.931,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Wouldn't that be true?","start":2744.931,"stop":2745.879,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We say it's one adjustment, Your Honor but --","start":2745.879,"stop":2747.476,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I know, but isn't -- wouldn't -- shouldn't it be the same that economic effect?","start":2747.476,"stop":2750.401,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If we had exchanged checks --","start":2750.401,"stop":2752.127,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2752.127,"stop":2752.205,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as Your Honor says and say there hadn't been any mortgage.","start":2752.205,"stop":2754.54,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2754.54,"stop":2755.005,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"- we would have ended up with checks totaling $20 million more than the checks we gave to the government, $20 million, that's the net.","start":2755.005,"stop":2765.028,"duration":10.02},{"text":"Now all we think --","start":2765.028,"stop":2765.611,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but the economic effects should be the same either way, shouldn't it?","start":2765.611,"stop":2770.197,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The economic effect is the same Your Honor, if you just recall that we are asking for the economic effect of a price adjustment regardless of the individual items that make it up.","start":2770.197,"stop":2782.277,"duration":12.08}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But if you would exchange checks -- if you had just exchanged checks, well you would have had the result of lines 1, 2, and 3, wouldn't you insofar as purchase price would have --","start":2782.277,"stop":2795.238,"duration":12.96}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, not 1, 2, and 3, we would not have.","start":2795.238,"stop":2799.679,"duration":4.44},{"text":"We would have ended up as I stated, we may have given them a check of $13,430,431.","start":2799.679,"stop":2806.057,"duration":6.38},{"text":"They would have given us the check for a million 495, a check for $2 million and 686, a check for $430,000 and if it (Voice Overlap) --","start":2806.057,"stop":2814.184,"duration":8.13}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And then they would have had to give you a $29 million credit on the purchase price?","start":2814.184,"stop":2819.186,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now well -- Your Honor, you didn't let me explain because there's additional check that they would have paid us.","start":2819.186,"stop":2824.501,"duration":5.32},{"text":"It's not here and that's the $11 million which you would get under sub-paragraph 1, as they have omitted entirely in Schedule 1, we would have gotten another $11 million check.","start":2824.501,"stop":2834.03,"duration":9.53},{"text":"Now that's a point that we say that brings us down and we would not have gotten $29 million, net.","start":2834.03,"stop":2842.062,"duration":8.03},{"text":"The difference would have not been $29 million, but we would have had another $11 million check if they don't recognize here and it's in the record.","start":2842.062,"stop":2851.432,"duration":9.37},{"text":"If Your Honor will simply refer to the stipulation.","start":2851.432,"stop":2855.131,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2855.131,"stop":2869.982,"duration":14.85}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Depreciation?","start":2869.982,"stop":2870.884,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2870.884,"stop":2871.596,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't get around that Your Honor.","start":2871.596,"stop":2872.896,"duration":1.3},{"text":"In fact, that's a way we base our computation of 46 million and the computation of the taxes are based on that.","start":2872.896,"stop":2880.729,"duration":7.83},{"text":"We don't say that it did have that fact.","start":2880.729,"stop":2882.996,"duration":2.27},{"text":"In fact, we recognized that effect.","start":2882.996,"stop":2885.657,"duration":2.66},{"text":"It was put in here for this very purpose to keep one of the parties from coming back later and saying you didn't' get.","start":2885.657,"stop":2891.842,"duration":6.18}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2891.842,"stop":2899.419,"duration":7.58}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no sir.","start":2899.419,"stop":2900.163,"duration":0.74},{"text":"That's not depreciation -- oh, excuse me Your Honor.","start":2900.163,"stop":2902.353,"duration":2.19},{"text":"This --","start":2902.353,"stop":2902.997,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2902.997,"stop":2904.429,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm talking to the -- if the -- it's on -- excuse me your Honor, let me --","start":2904.429,"stop":2918.926,"duration":14.5}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2918.926,"stop":2920.642,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"On 47, that's right.","start":2920.642,"stop":2921.862,"duration":1.22},{"text":"So now, that's under sub-paragraph 1 of your computation.","start":2921.862,"stop":2925.887,"duration":4.03},{"text":"This has nothing to do with depreciation, I'm sorry I didn't make that clear.","start":2925.887,"stop":2929.776,"duration":3.89},{"text":"This $11 million is entirely ignored in Schedule 1 of the government, but that's the first credit to which we were entitled and it's part of the net credits under sub-paragraph 8.","start":2929.776,"stop":2946.041,"duration":16.27}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2946.041,"stop":2947.431,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":2947.431,"stop":2948.422,"duration":0.99},{"text":"If you go down credit on page 47, the last item Your Honor.","start":2948.422,"stop":2953.918,"duration":5.5},{"text":"Credits in favor of maritime, charter hire credited them a 13 million.","start":2953.918,"stop":2957.752,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2957.752,"stop":2960.561,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it reduce as 11 million but when you add the 2 million interest, the 1 million charter hire, I'd like to ask the government where we got depreciation on those four vessels, they treated as having been owed.","start":2960.561,"stop":2971.873,"duration":11.31}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2971.873,"stop":2976.195,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's just one check.","start":2976.195,"stop":2977.327,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2977.327,"stop":2979.206,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2979.206,"stop":2979.923,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I know that [Inaudible]","start":2979.923,"stop":2992.076,"duration":12.15}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2992.076,"stop":2993.25,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":2993.25,"stop":3000.308,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"John W. McConnell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh!","start":3000.308,"stop":3000.506,"duration":0.2},{"text":"Well, I was answering Mr. Justice White about individual checks for each credit.","start":3000.506,"stop":3005.386,"duration":4.88},{"text":"That's the reason I said I wanted a check for $11 million, $2 million, $1 million and $430,000.","start":3005.386,"stop":3012.675,"duration":7.29},{"text":"Then I'll give them back a check for $13 million.","start":3012.675,"stop":3016.525,"duration":3.85},{"text":"I was just answering his point that if we gave individual checks for each item there, but the net is as shown on 47 which is a stipulation of the parties here.","start":3016.525,"stop":3028.979,"duration":12.45},{"text":"And in conclusion, we give effect the 9(c) 1, but we give it the effect desired and the effect that Congress intended, but we say look back in these sub-paragraphs and look for one adjustment and to get back to Mr. Justice White, we paid $26 million which is more than the statutory sales price, we're not asking of anything except what the government gave to this taxpayer after having put out $50 million, not knowing whether it ever have reduction, they pass the statute, we're simply asking for the benefits which Congress intended to give this taxpayer to put out some money, not in reliance on any price adjustment.","start":3028.979,"stop":3068.817,"duration":39.84},{"text":"Thank you gentlemen.","start":3068.817,"stop":3070.195,"duration":1.38}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Apr  26 - 27, 1965","petitioner":"Waterman Steamship Corporation","respondent":"United States","docket":"245","citation":"381US252(1965)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/381/252","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"May 17, 1965"}